{"title_page": "Corliss Palmer", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          =  Corliss Palmer\n| image         =  Corliss Palmer ca. 1922.jpg\n| alt           =  \n| caption       = Palmer {{circa}} 1922\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1899|07|25}} \n| birth_place   =  [[Edison, Georgia|Edison]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date    =  {{Death date and age|1952|08|27|1899|07|25}} \n| death_place= [[Camarillo, California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| spouse= {{marriage|[[Eugene V. Brewster]]|1926|1931|end=div}}\n| resting_place= [[Woodlawn Memorial Cemetery, Santa Monica]]\n| resting_place_coordinates= {{coord| 34.0178 | 118.4758 }}\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1922\u20131931\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Corliss Palmer''' (July 25, 1899{{efn|Though some sources note Palmer's birth year as 1902, according to NARA microfilm publication T623 (Washington, D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1972.); FHL microfilm 1,240,181, she was born in 1899 and, at the 1902 census, resided in Brooks, Georgia.<ref name=fs/>}}  \u2013 August 27, 1952) was an American [[silent film]] actress and model. She first came to public attention after winning ''[[Motion Picture Magazine]]''{{'}}s Fame and Fortune Contest in 1920, upon which she was deemed the \"most beautiful girl in America.\" She would go on to appear in a total of sixteen films between 1922 and 1931.\n\n==Early life==\nPalmer was born to Luther and Julia Palmer in [[Edison, Georgia]] on July 25, 1899. She had an older sister, Mary,<ref name=\"fs\">\"United States Census, 1900,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:M3FG-NDS : accessed 22 June 2017), Helen Palmer in household of Luther Palmer, Militia District Quitman town, Brooks, Georgia, United States; citing enumeration district (ED) 6, sheet 16A, family 296, NARA microfilm publication T623 (Washington, D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1972.); FHL microfilm 1,240,181.</ref> younger brothers, Hoke and Grady, and a younger sister, Ennis.<ref>\"United States Census, 1920,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:MJ8C-MSM : accessed 22 June 2017), Grady Palmer in household of J M Simmone, Macon Ward 4, Bibb, Georgia, United States; citing ED 43, sheet 7B, line 98, family 183, NARA microfilm publication T625 (Washington D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1992), roll 235; FHL microfilm 1,820,235.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1920, Palmer entered the \"Fame and Fortune Contest\" advertised in ''[[Motion Picture Magazine]]''. She won the contest, and was heralded by the magazine as the \"most beautiful girl in America.\"<ref name=mp1/> The magazine's publisher, [[Eugene V. Brewster]], allowed Palmer significant publicity in the magazine, and began to promote her as she embarked on a film career. Between 1921 and 1923, ''Motion Picture Magazine'' published a total of twenty-three articles on Palmer, while its sister publication, ''[[Motion Picture Classic]]'', published an additional story on the actress.{{sfn|Slide|2010|p=16}} Palmer also had a cosmetic line named after her featuring Peach Bloom Face Powder, created by the Wilton Chemical Company in New York City,<ref name=mp1>{{cite journal|work=[[Motion Picture Magazine|Motion Picture]]|volume=24|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mxQXAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=corliss+palmer+most+beautiful&source=bl&ots=TI6YmuSVkZ&sig=YRo7s6t0VYWkF-APAr6bsqjJH2E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZxPDx5dDUAhVI2WMKHfWBD1oQ6AEIWDAO#v=onepage&q=corliss%20palmer%20most%20beautiful&f=false|page=100|title=Corliss Palmer Powder|via=[[Google Books]]}} {{open access}}</ref> and also appeared on the cover of ''Beauty'', a women's magazine.<ref name=mp1/>\n\nShe made her film debut in the short ''From Farm to Fame'', documenting her public notoriety after winning the contest, followed by an acting role in ''[[Her Second Chance (1926 film)|Her Second Chance]]'' (1926).{{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n\nAfter ending her acting career in 1931, Palmer continued to model cosmetics as well as fashions for a local department store.<ref>{{cite news|author=Shaffer, Rosalind|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 10, 1934|page=6|title=Corliss Palmer, Georgia Peach, a Changed Girl|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1934/06/10/page/72/article/display-ad-51-no-title}}</ref><ref>Redmond, Jennifer Ann (2018). SOUTHERN BELLE TO HOLLYWOOD HELL: Corliss Palmer and her Scandalous Rise and Fall. BearManor Media.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married Eugene V. Brewster in October 1926.{{sfn|Slide|2010|pages=16\u201317}} The couple lived on a $500,000 estate in [[Morristown, New Jersey]], but were forced to relocate to a one-bedroom apartment in [[Hollywood]], [[California]] in 1931 after Brewster's estate was squandered when his former wife sued him for alienation of affection.{{sfn|Slide|2010|p=16}} The couple would divorce in 1931.{{sfn|Slide|2010|p=16}}\n\nAfter her divorce, Palmer became an [[alcoholism|alcoholic]], and on January 31, 1933, was committed to a hospital in [[San Francisco]] under the pseudonym Edith Mason,<ref name=portsmouth>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/59043073/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|title=\"I Chased the Rainbow\u2014and Now Look at Me!\" \u2013 What Corliss Palmer Brewster, Prize Beauty, Told the Doctors When She Woke Up and Found Herself in a Hospital | date=March 12, 1933|work=Portsmouth Daily Times| location=Portsmouth, Ohio|page=11}}</ref> a name she had adopted in an attempt to revitalize her film career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/29469315/|work=The Amarillo-Globe Times|location=Amarillo, Texas|page=7|date=February 1, 1933|title=Raving Woman Former Star? Beauty Rushed to Hospital May Be Corliss Palmer|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> It was noted in March 12, 1933 article in the ''[[Portsmouth Daily Times]]'' that Palmer \"had been drinking steadily for several days,\" and the hospital staff \"feared she might harm herself or set fire to her room.\"<ref name=portsmouth/> Palmer would spend the latter half of her life in psychiatric institutions.{{sfn|Slide|2010|pages=250\u201351}} She died in 1952 in [[Camarillo, California]].{{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Lost films}}\n| Denotes [[lost film]]s\n|}\n[[File:From Farm to Fame poster.jpg|thumb|Film poster]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1922\n| ''From Farm to Fame''\n| {{N/A}}\n| [[Short film]]\n| style=text-align:center|\n|-\n| 1926\n|  style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Her Second Chance (1926 film)|Her Second Chance]]'' {{dagger}}\n| Nancy\n|  \n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1926\n| ''[[Bromo and Juliet]]''\n| Madge\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| ''[[The Return of Boston Blackie]]''\n| Sylvia Markham\n| \n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Wlaschin| |p=191}}\n|-\n| 1927\n|  style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[A Man's Past]] '' {{dagger}}\n| Sylvia Cabot\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1927 \n| ''[[Polly of the Movies]]''\n| Lisa Smith\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Honeymoon Hate]]'' {{dagger}}\n| Mrs. Fremont Gage I\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[The Noose (film)|The Noose]]''\n| Cabaret Girl\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[Into the Night (1928 film)|Into the Night]]'' \n| Mrs. Harding\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[The Night Bird]]''\n| Blonde\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''George Washington Cohen''\n| Mrs. Gorman\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''Trial Marriage''\n| {{n/a|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''Scarlet Youth''\n| {{N/A|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[Clothes Make the Woman]]''\n| {{n/a|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1929\n| ''Sex Madness''\n| {{n/a|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&retailCheck=&Type=PN&CatID=DATABIN_CAST&ID=34111&AN_ID=&searchedFor=Corliss_Palmer_|work=[[American Film Institute]]|title=Abbreviated View of Movie Page: Sex Madness (1929)|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1929\n| ''[[Broadway Fever]]''\n| Lila Leroy\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n'''Explanatory notes'''\n{{noteslist}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last1=Redmond |first1=Jennifer Ann |title=Southern Belle to Hollywood Hell: Corliss Palmer and her Scandalous Rise and Fall |date=2018 |publisher=BearManor Media |isbn=978-1629333410||ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lowe|first=Denise|title=An Encyclopedic Dictionary of Women in Early American Films, 1895-1930|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-789-01843-4|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9790874369709_b7n2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Slide|first=Anthony|title=Inside the Hollywood Fan Magazine: A History of Star Makers, Fabricators, and Gossip Mongers|publisher=University of Mississippi Press|year=2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5hDG6auRCJ4C&dq=corliss+palmer+sister&source=gbs_navlinks_s|isbn=978-1-604-73414-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wlaschin|first=Ken|title=Silent Mystery and Detective Movies: A Comprehensive Filmography|publisher=McFarland|year=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U5UZDgAAQBAJ&dq=corliss+palmer&source=gbs_navlinks_s|isbn=978-0-786-44350-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Corliss Palmer}}\n*[http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&retailCheck=&Type=PN&CatID=DATABIN_CAST&ID=34111&AN_ID=&searchedFor=Corliss_Palmer_ Corliss Palmer] at the [[American Film Institute]] catalog\n*{{IMDb name|0658176}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palmer, Corliss}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Female models from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Calhoun County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Memorial Cemetery, Santa Monica]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          =  Corliss Palmer\n| image         =  Corliss Palmer ca. 1922.jpg\n| alt           =  \n| caption       = Palmer {{circa}} 1922\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1899|07|25}} \n| birth_place   =  [[Edison, Georgia|Edison]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date    =  {{Death date and age|1952|08|27|1899|07|25}} \n| death_place= [[Camarillo, California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| spouse= {{marriage|[[Eugene V. Brewster]]|1926|1931|end=div}}\n| resting_place= [[Woodlawn Memorial Cemetery, Santa Monica]]\n| resting_place_coordinates= {{coord| 34.0178 | 118.4758 }}\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1922\u20131931\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Corliss Palmer''' (July 25, 1899{{efn|Though some sources note Palmer's birth year as 1902, according to NARA microfilm publication T623 (Washington, D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1972.); FHL microfilm 1,240,181, she was born in 1899 and, at the 1902 census, resided in Brooks, Georgia.<ref name=fs/>}}  \u2013 August 27, 1952) was an American [[silent film]] actress and model. She first came to public attention after winning ''[[Motion Picture Magazine]]''{{'}}s Fame and Fortune Contest in 1920, upon which she was deemed the \"most beautiful girl in America.\" She would go on to appear in a total of sixteen films between 1922 and 1931.\n\n==Early life==\nPalmer was born to Luther and Julia Palmer in [[Edison, Georgia]] on July 25, 1899. She had an older sister, Mary,<ref name=\"fs\">\"United States Census, 1900,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:M3FG-NDS : accessed 22 June 2017), Helen Palmer in household of Luther Palmer, Militia District Quitman town, Brooks, Georgia, United States; citing enumeration district (ED) 6, sheet 16A, family 296, NARA microfilm publication T623 (Washington, D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1972.); FHL microfilm 1,240,181.</ref> younger brothers, Hoke and Grady, and a younger sister, Ennis.<ref>\"United States Census, 1920,\" database with images, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:MJ8C-MSM : accessed 22 June 2017), Grady Palmer in household of J M Simmone, Macon Ward 4, Bibb, Georgia, United States; citing ED 43, sheet 7B, line 98, family 183, NARA microfilm publication T625 (Washington D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 1992), roll 235; FHL microfilm 1,820,235.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1920, Palmer entered the \"Fame and Fortune Contest\" advertised in ''[[Motion Picture Magazine]]''. She won the contest, and was heralded by the magazine as the \"most beautiful girl in America.\"<ref name=mp1/> The magazine's publisher, [[Eugene V. Brewster]], allowed Palmer significant publicity in the magazine, and began to promote her as she embarked on a film career. Between 1921 and 1923, ''Motion Picture Magazine'' published a total of twenty-three articles on Palmer, while its sister publication, ''[[Motion Picture Classic]]'', published an additional story on the actress.{{sfn|Slide|2010|p=16}} Palmer also had a cosmetic line named after her featuring Peach Bloom Face Powder, created by the Wilton Chemical Company in New York City,<ref name=mp1>{{cite journal|work=[[Motion Picture Magazine|Motion Picture]]|volume=24|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mxQXAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=corliss+palmer+most+beautiful&source=bl&ots=TI6YmuSVkZ&sig=YRo7s6t0VYWkF-APAr6bsqjJH2E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZxPDx5dDUAhVI2WMKHfWBD1oQ6AEIWDAO#v=onepage&q=corliss%20palmer%20most%20beautiful&f=false|page=100|title=Corliss Palmer Powder|via=[[Google Books]]}} {{open access}}</ref> and also appeared on the cover of ''Beauty'', a women's magazine.<ref name=mp1/>\n\nShe made her film debut in the short ''From Farm to Fame'', documenting her public notoriety after winning the contest, followed by an acting role in ''[[Her Second Chance (1926 film)|Her Second Chance]]'' (1926).{{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n\nAfter ending her acting career in 1931, Palmer continued to model cosmetics as well as fashions for a local department store.<ref>{{cite news|author=Shaffer, Rosalind|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=June 10, 1934|page=6|title=Corliss Palmer, Georgia Peach, a Changed Girl|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1934/06/10/page/72/article/display-ad-51-no-title}}</ref><ref>Redmond, Jennifer Ann (2018). SOUTHERN BELLE TO HOLLYWOOD HELL: Corliss Palmer and her Scandalous Rise and Fall. BearManor Media.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married Eugene V. Brewster in October 1926.{{sfn|Slide|2010|pages=16\u201317}} The couple lived on a $500,000 estate in [[Morristown, New Jersey]], but were forced to relocate to a one-bedroom apartment in [[Hollywood]], [[California]] in 1931 after Brewster's estate was squandered when his former wife sued him for alienation of affection.{{sfn|Slide|2010|p=16}} The couple would divorce in 1931.{{sfn|Slide|2010|p=16}}\n\nAfter her divorce, Palmer became an [[alcoholism|alcoholic]], and on January 31, 1933, was committed to a hospital in [[San Francisco]] under the pseudonym Edith Mason,<ref name=portsmouth>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/59043073/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|title=\"I Chased the Rainbow\u2014and Now Look at Me!\" \u2013 What Corliss Palmer Brewster, Prize Beauty, Told the Doctors When She Woke Up and Found Herself in a Hospital | date=March 12, 1933|work=Portsmouth Daily Times| location=Portsmouth, Ohio|page=11}}</ref> a name she had adopted in an attempt to revitalize her film career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/29469315/|work=The Amarillo-Globe Times|location=Amarillo, Texas|page=7|date=February 1, 1933|title=Raving Woman Former Star? Beauty Rushed to Hospital May Be Corliss Palmer|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> It was noted in March 12, 1933 article in the ''[[Portsmouth Daily Times]]'' that Palmer \"had been drinking steadily for several days,\" and the hospital staff \"feared she might harm herself or set fire to her room.\"<ref name=portsmouth/> Palmer would spend the latter half of her life in psychiatric institutions.{{sfn|Slide|2010|pages=250\u201351}} She died in 1952 in [[Camarillo, California]].{{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Lost films}}\n| Denotes [[lost film]]s\n|}\n[[File:From Farm to Fame poster.jpg|thumb|Film poster]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1922\n| ''From Farm to Fame''\n| {{N/A}}\n| [[Short film]]\n| style=text-align:center|\n|-\n| 1926\n|  style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Her Second Chance (1926 film)|Her Second Chance]]'' {{dagger}}\n| Nancy\n|  \n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1926\n| ''[[Bromo and Juliet]]''\n| Madge\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| ''[[The Return of Boston Blackie]]''\n| Sylvia Markham\n| \n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Wlaschin| |p=191}}\n|-\n| 1927\n|  style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[A Man's Past]] '' {{dagger}}\n| Sylvia Cabot\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1927 \n| ''[[Polly of the Movies]]''\n| Lisa Smith\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| ''[[Honeymoon Hate]]'' {{dagger}}\n| Mrs. Fremont Gage I\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[The Noose (film)|The Noose]]''\n| Cabaret Girl\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[Into the Night (1928 film)|Into the Night]]'' \n| Mrs. Harding\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[The Night Bird]]''\n| Blonde\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''George Washington Cohen''\n| Mrs. Gorman\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''Trial Marriage''\n| {{n/a|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''Scarlet Youth''\n| {{N/A|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| ''[[Clothes Make the Woman]]''\n| {{n/a|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n| 1929\n| ''Sex Madness''\n| {{n/a|align=left}}\n|\n| style=text-align:center| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&retailCheck=&Type=PN&CatID=DATABIN_CAST&ID=34111&AN_ID=&searchedFor=Corliss_Palmer_|work=[[American Film Institute]]|title=Abbreviated View of Movie Page: Sex Madness (1929)|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1929\n| ''[[Broadway Fever]]''\n| Lila Leroy\n|\n| style=text-align:center| {{sfn|Lowe|2005|p=520}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n'''Explanatory notes'''\n{{noteslist}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last1=Redmond |first1=Jennifer Ann |title=Southern Belle to Hollywood Hell: Corliss Palmer and her Scandalous Rise and Fall |date=2018 |publisher=BearManor Media |isbn=978-1629333410||ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lowe|first=Denise|title=An Encyclopedic Dictionary of Women in Early American Films, 1895-1930|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-789-01843-4|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9790874369709_b7n2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Slide|first=Anthony|title=Inside the Hollywood Fan Magazine: A History of Star Makers, Fabricators, and Gossip Mongers|publisher=University of Mississippi Press|year=2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5hDG6auRCJ4C&dq=corliss+palmer+sister&source=gbs_navlinks_s|isbn=978-1-604-73414-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wlaschin|first=Ken|title=Silent Mystery and Detective Movies: A Comprehensive Filmography|publisher=McFarland|year=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U5UZDgAAQBAJ&dq=corliss+palmer&source=gbs_navlinks_s|isbn=978-0-786-44350-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Corliss Palmer}}\n*[http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&retailCheck=&Type=PN&CatID=DATABIN_CAST&ID=34111&AN_ID=&searchedFor=Corliss_Palmer_ Corliss Palmer] at the [[American Film Institute]] catalog\n*{{IMDb name|0658176}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palmer, Corliss}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Female models from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:People from Calhoun County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Burials at Woodlawn Memorial Cemetery, Santa Monica]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:American film actressesusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corliss_Palmer"}
{"title_page": "Natacha Rambova", "text_new": "{{short description|20th-century American film personality and fashion designer}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Natacha Rambova\n| image = File:Natacha Rambova, 1925.png\n| caption  = Rambova in 1925\n| birth_name = Winifred Kimball Shaughnessy\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1897|01|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1966|06|05|1897|01|19}}\n| death_place = [[Pasadena, California]], U.S.\n| other_names  =  {{plainlist|Winifred Hudnut\n* Winifred de Wolfe\n* Natacha Valentino\n* Natacha de Urz\u00e0iz\n}}\n| height= {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m}}\n| occupation = {{hlist|[[Costume design|Costume]] and [[Scenic design|set]] designer | dancer | actress | academic }}\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Rudolph Valentino]]|1923|1925|end=div}}<br>{{marriage|\u00c1lvaro de Urz\u00e1iz|1932|1957|end=annulled}}\n| relatives = [[Heber C. Kimball]] (great-grandfather)\n}}\n\n'''Natacha Rambova''' (born '''Winifred Kimball Shaughnessy''', January 19, 1897 \u2013 June 5, 1966) was an American film costume designer and set designer, and occasional actress who was active in Hollywood in the 1920s. In her later life, she abandoned design to pursue other interests, specifically [[Egyptology]], a subject on which she became a published scholar in the 1950s.\n\nRambova was born into a prominent family in Salt Lake City who were members of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]. She was raised in San Francisco and educated in England before beginning her career as a dancer, performing under Russian ballet choreographer [[Theodore Kosloff]] in New York City. She relocated to Los Angeles at age 19, where she became an established costume designer for Hollywood film productions. It was there she became acquainted with actor [[Rudolph Valentino]], with whom she had a two-year marriage from 1923 to 1925. Rambova's association with Valentino afforded her a widespread celebrity typically afforded to actors.<ref name=picturing>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screeningthepast.com/2015/08/picturing-natacha-rambova-design-and-celebrity-performance-in-the-1920s/|work=Screening the Past|title=Picturing Natacha Rambova: Design and Celebrity Performance in the 1920s|author=Cook, Pam|accessdate=November 9, 2017|date=August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819101602/http://www.screeningthepast.com/2015/08/picturing-natacha-rambova-design-and-celebrity-performance-in-the-1920s/|archivedate=August 19, 2016}}</ref> Although they shared many interests such as art, poetry and [[spiritualism]], his colleagues felt that she exercised too much control over his work and blamed her for several expensive career flops.\n\nAfter divorcing Valentino in 1925, Rambova operated her own clothing store in Manhattan before moving to Europe and marrying the aristocrat \u00c1lvaro de Urz\u00e1iz in 1932. It was during this time that she visited Egypt, and developed a fascination with the country that remained for the rest of her life. Rambova spent her later years studying Egyptology and earned two [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation|Mellon Grant]]s to travel there and study Egyptian symbols and belief systems. She served as the editor of the first three volumes of ''Egyptian Religious Texts and Representations'' (1954\u20137) by Alexandre Piankoff, also contributing a chapter on symbology in the third volume. She died in 1966 in California of a heart attack while working on a manuscript examining patterns within the texts in the [[Pyramid of Unas]].\n\nRambova has been noted by fashion and art historians for her unique costume designs that drew on and synthesized a variety of influences, as well as her dedication to historical accuracy in crafting them. Academics have also cited her interpretive contributions to the field of Egyptology as significant. In popular culture, Rambova has been depicted in several films and television series, figuring significantly in the Valentino biopics ''[[The Legend of Valentino]]'' (1975), in which she was portrayed by [[Yvette Mimieux]], and [[Ken Russell]]'s ''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'' (1977) by [[Michelle Phillips]]. She was also featured in a fictionalized narrative in the network series ''[[American Horror Story: Hotel]]'' (2015), portrayed by [[Alexandra Daddario]].\n\n==Early life==\nRambova was born Winifred Kimball Shaughnessy on January 19, 1897, in Salt Lake City, Utah.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=4G4uCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=winifred+kimball+shaughnessy+january+1897#v=onepage&q=winifred%2520kimball%2520shaughnessy%2520january%25201897&f=false |title=Creating the Illusion (Turner Classic Movies): A Fashionable History of Hollywood Costume Designers |last=Jorgensen |first=Jay |last2=Scoggins |first2=Donald L. |date=2015-10-06 |publisher=Running Press |isbn=9780762458073 |pages=28 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Her father, Michael Shaughnessy, was an Irish Catholic from New York City who fought for the Union during the [[American Civil War]] and then worked in the mining industry. Her mother, Winifred Shaughnessy (n\u00e9e Kimball),{{sfn|Kimball|1986|p=311}} was the granddaughter of [[Heber C. Kimball]]  a member of the first presidency of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]],{{efn|Biographer and descendant Stanley Kimball notes in his biography ''Heber C. Kimball: Mormon Patriarch and Pioneer'' (1981) that Rambova's great-grandfather, Heber, was a sixth-generation American descended from English immigrants in the New England colony.{{sfn|Kimball|1986|p=4}} }} and was raised in a prominent Salt Lake City family.<ref name=lesko/> At her father's wishes, Rambova was baptized a Catholic at the [[Cathedral of the Madeleine (Salt Lake City, Utah)|Cathedral of the Madeleine]] in Salt Lake City in June 1897,{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=28}} though she later was baptized a member of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] at the urging of her mother at age eight.{{sfn|Quinn|2001|pages=173\u20135}} \n[[File:Natacha Rambova 1916 passport photo.png|thumb|upright|right|Rambova's 1916 passport photograph|alt=A young woman facing a camera, staring toward the right]]\n\nRambova's parents had a tumultuous relationship: Her father was an alcoholic, and often sold her mother's possessions to pay off gambling debts.{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=28\u20139}} This led Winifred (senior) to divorce Shaughnessy in 1900 and relocate with Rambova to San Francisco.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=29}} There, she remarried  to Edgar de Wolfe in 1907.{{sfn|Sparke|2005|p=344}} During her childhood, Rambova spent summer vacations at the Villa Trianon in [[Le Chesnay]], France with Edgar's sister, the French designer [[Elsie de Wolfe]].{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=92}}{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=37\u20139}} The marriage between Winifred (senior) and Edgar de Wolfe was short-lived, and she again remarried, this time to millionaire perfume mogul [[Richard Hudnut]].{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=32}} Rambova was adopted by her new stepfather, making her legal name Winifred Hudnut.{{sfn|Kotowski|2014|p=90}} Rambova was given the nickname \"Wink\" by her aunt Teresa to distinguish her from her mother because of their shared name.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=28}} She also sometimes went by Winifred de Wolfe, after her former step-aunt Elsie, with whom she maintained a relationship after her mother's divorce from Edgar.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=129}}\n\nA rebellious teenager, Rambova was sent by her mother to Leatherhead Court, a boarding school in [[Surrey]], [[England]].{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=83}}{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=130}}{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=34\u20138}} In her schooling, she became fascinated by [[Greek mythology]],<ref name=lesko>{{cite web|publisher=Brown University|work=Breaking Ground: Women in Old World Archaeology|url=https://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Rambova_Natacha.pdf|title=Natacha Rambova|accessdate=November 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504031045/https://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Rambova_Natacha.pdf|archivedate=May 4, 2006}}</ref> and also proved especially gifted at ballet.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=130}} After seeing [[Anna Pavlova]] in a production of ''[[Swan Lake]]'' in Paris with her former step-aunt Elsie, Rambova decided she wanted to pursue a career as a [[Ballet dancer|ballerina]].{{sfn|Lambert|1997|p=234}} Her family had encouraged her to study ballet purely as a social grace, and were appalled when she chose it as her career. Her aunt Teresa, however, was supportive, and took Rambova to New York City, where she studied under the Russian ballet dancer and choreographer [[Theodore Kosloff]] in his Imperial Russian Ballet Company.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=131}} While dancing under Kosloff, she adopted the Russian-inspired stage name Natacha Rambova.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=224}} Standing at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m}}, Rambova was too tall to be a classical ballerina, but was given leading parts by the then-32-year-old Kosloff, who soon became her lover.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=224}}{{sfn|Lambert|1997|p=232}} Rambova's mother was outraged upon discovering the affair as Rambova was 17 years old at the time, and she tried to have Kosloff deported on [[statutory rape]] charges.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=46}}{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=28}} Rambova retaliated against her mother by fleeing abroad, and her mother ultimately agreed to her continuing to perform with the company.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=224}}\n\n==Career==\n===Design in film===\n[[File:Forbidden Fruit (1921) costume sketch by Natacha Rambova.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Costume concept for ''Forbidden Fruit'' (1921), designed and drawn by Rambova|alt=Illustration of woman in ornate costume]]\nAround 1917, Kosloff was hired by [[Cecil B. DeMille]] as a performer and costume designer for DeMille's Hollywood films, after which he and Rambova relocated from New York to Los Angeles.{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=59\u201360}} Rambova carried out much of the creative work as well as the historical research for Kosloff, and he then stole her sketches and claimed credit for these as his own.{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=28}} When Kosloff started work for fellow-Russian film producer [[Alla Nazimova]] at Metro Pictures Corporation (later MGM) in 1919, he sent Rambova to present some designs. Nazimova requested some alterations, and was impressed when Rambova was able to make these changes immediately in her own hand. Nazimova offered Rambova a position on her production staff as an art director and costume designer, proposing a wage of up to [[US dollar|USD]]$5,000 per picture ({{Inflation|US|5000|1920|fmt=eq}}).{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=225}} Rambova immediately began working for Nazimova on the comedy film ''[[Billions (film)|Billions]]'' (1920), for which she supplied the costumes and served as art director.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}} She also designed the costumes for two Cecil DeMille films in 1920: ''[[Why Change Your Wife?]]'' and ''[[Something to Think About]]''.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=57}} The following year, she served as the art director on the DeMille production ''[[Forbidden Fruit (1921 film)|Forbidden Fruit]]'' (1921), in which she designed (with [[Mitchell Leisen]]) an elaborate costume for a Cinderella-inspired fantasy sequence.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=57}}\n\nWhile working on her second project for Nazimova\u2014''Aphrodite'', which never was filmed{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=238}}\u2014Rambova revealed to Kosloff that she planned on leaving him. During the ensuing argument, he attempted to kill her,{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=67}} shooting at her with a shotgun.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=63}} The gun fired into Rambova's leg, and the bullet lodged above her knee.{{sfn|McLellan|2000|p=27}} Rambova fled the Hollywood apartment she shared with Kosloff to the set of ''Aphrodite'', where a cameraman helped her remove the [[Shotgun shell#Bird shot|birdshot]] from her leg.{{sfn|McLellan|2000|p=27}} Despite the nature of the incident, she continued to live with Kosloff for some time.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=67}}\n\nStylistically, Rambova favored designers such as [[Paul Poiret]],{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=28}} [[L\u00e9on Bakst]],<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The New Yorker|page=120|title=Valentino|series=Goings On About Town|year=1977|volume=53}}</ref> and [[Aubrey Beardsley]].{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=28}} She specialized in \"exotic\" and \"foreign\" effects in both costume and stage design. For costumes she favored bright colors, baubles, bangles, shimmering draped fabrics, sparkles, and feathers.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=131}} She also strived for historical accuracy in her costume and set designs. As noted in ''[[The Moving Picture World]]''{{'}}s review of 1917's ''[[The Woman God Forgot]]'' (Rambova's first film project): \"To the student of history the accuracy of the exteriors, interiors, costumes, and accessories ... [the film] will make strong appeal.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[The Moving Picture World]]|date=November 17, 1917|url=https://archive.org/details/movpicwor342movi|via=The [[Internet Archive|Archive.org]]|author=Keyser, E.T.|title=The Woman God Forgot|series=Reviews of Current Productions|p=1035}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with Rudolph Valentino===\n[[File:Rudolph Valentino and Natacha Rambova - Valentino As I Knew Him.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.95|Rambova with Valentino in 1925|alt=Man and woman standing together, looking into the camera]]\nIn 1921, Rambova was introduced to actor [[Rudolph Valentino]] on the set of Nazimova's ''Uncharted Seas'' (1921).{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=28}} She and Valentino subsequently worked together on ''[[Camille (1921 film)|Camille]]'' (1921),{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=70}} a film which was a financial failure and resulted in Metro Pictures terminating their contract with Nazimova.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=227}} While making the film, however, Rambova and Valentino became romantically involved. Although Valentino was still married to American film actress [[Jean Acker]], he and Rambova moved in together within a year, having formed a relationship based more on friendship and shared interests than on emotional or professional rapport. They then had to pretend to separate until Valentino's divorce was finalized, and married on May 13, 1922 in Mexicali, Mexico, an event described by Rambova as \"wonderful ... even though it did cause many worries and heartaches later.\"{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=61}} However, the law required a year to pass before remarriage, and Valentino was jailed for [[bigamy]], having to be bailed out by friends.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=62}} They legally remarried on March 14, 1923 in [[Crown Point, Indiana]].{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=133}}\n\nBoth Rambova and Valentino were [[spiritualism|spiritualists]], and they frequently visited psychics and took part in s\u00e9ances and [[automatic writing]].{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=74}} Valentino wrote a book of poetry ''Daydreams'' with many poems about Rambova.{{sfn|Leider|2003|pages=241\u20132}} When it came to domestic life, Valentino and Rambova turned out to hold very different views. Valentino cherished Old World ideals of a woman being a housewife and mother, while Rambova was intent on maintaining a career and had no intention of being a housewife.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=282}} Valentino was known as an excellent cook, while actress Patsy Ruth Miller suspected Rambova didn't know \"how to make burnt fudge,\" although the truth was she did occasionally bake and was an excellent seamstress.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=198}} Valentino wanted children, but Rambova did not.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=177}}{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=30}}\n{{quotebox|width=19%|bgcolor=lavender|align=right|quote=He knew what I was when I married him. I have been working since I was seventeen. Homes and babies are all very nice, but you can't have them and a career as well. I intended, and intend, to have a career and Valentino knew it. If he wants a housewife, he'll have to look again.|source=\u2013Rambova on Valentino during the dissolution of their marriage{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=172}} }}\n\nWhile her association with Valentino lent Rambova a celebrity typically afforded to actors, their professional collaborations showed-up their differences more than their similarities, and she did not contribute to any of his successful films in spite of serving as his manager.{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|pages=29\u201330}} In ''[[The Young Rajah]]'' (1922){{sfn|Leider|2003|p=215}} she designed authentic Indian costumes that tended to compromise his [[Latin lover (stereotype)|Latin lover]] image, and the film was a major flop.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=215}} She also supported his one-man strike against [[Famous Players-Lasky]], which left him temporarily banned from movie work.{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=29}} In the interval, they performed a promotional dance-tour for Mineralava Beauty Products, to keep his name in the spotlight, though when they reached her hometown of Salt Lake City, and she was billed as \"The Little Pigtailed Shaughnessy Girl\", Rambova was deeply insulted.{{sfn|Leider|2003|p=249}} In 1923, Rambova helped design the costumes for friend [[Alla Nazimova]] in ''[[Salom\u00e9 (1923 film)|Salom\u00e9]]'', inspired by the work of [[Aubrey Beardsley]].{{Sfn|Mahar|2008|p=175}} Beginning in February 1924, she accompanied Valentino on a trip abroad that was profiled in 26 installments published ''Movie Weekly'' over the course of six months.{{sfn|Williams|2013|pages=93\u20134}}\n\nRambova's later work with Valentino was characterised by elaborate and costly preparations for films that either flopped or never manifested. These included ''[[Monsieur Beaucaire (1924 film)|Monsieur Beaucaire]]'', ''The Sainted Devil'', and ''The Hooded Falcon'' (a film that Rambova co-wrote, but was never realized).{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|pages=238, 250}} By this time, critics and the press were beginning to blame Rambova's excessive control for these failures.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|pages=249\u201350}}{{sfn|Klepper|2005|p=378}} [[United Artists]] went so far as to offer Valentino an exclusive contract with the stipulation that Rambova had no negotiating power, and was disallowed from even visiting the sets of his films.{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=29}} After this, Rambova was offered $30,000 to create a film of her choosing, which resulted in the production of ''[[What Price Beauty?]]'', a drama which she co-produced and co-wrote.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=234}} In 1925, Rambova and Valentino separated, and an acrimonious divorce ensued.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=234}}\n\nAfter the divorce proceedings began, Rambova moved on to other ventures: On March 2, 1926, she patented a doll she had designed with a \"combined coverlet\",<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Popular Science]]|title=Invention\u2013Hobby of Great Men|p=136|date=January 1928|volume=112|number=1|issn=0161-7370}}</ref><ref>{{cite patent\n| country=US | number=1575263 |title=Combined coverlet and doll|pubdate= March 2, 1926.|fdate= March 6, 1924|inventor=Guglielmi, Winifred (Rambova, N.)|url=https://www.google.com/patents/US1575263}}</ref> and also produced and starred in her own picture, ''Do Clothes Make the Woman?'' with [[Clive Brook]] (now lost).{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=234}} However, the distributor took the opportunity to bill her as 'Mrs. Valentino' and changed the title to ''[[When Love Grows Cold]]''; Rambova was horrified by the title change.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=234}} The film did garner press due to it being Rambova's first screen credit, however. An Oregon newspaper teased before a screening: \"Natacha Rambova (Mrs. Rudolph Valentino) ... So much has been written of this remarkable lady who won and lost the heart of the great Valentino that everyone wants to see her. Tonight is your opportunity to do so.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=The Klamath News|location=[[Klamath Falls, Oregon]]|title=When Love Grows Cold|page=5|date=December 15, 1926|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/92127654/}}</ref> The film, however, was not well received by critics; a review in ''[[Picture Play (magazine)|Picture Play]]'' deemed the film \"the poorest picture of the month, or of almost any month, for that matter,\" adding: \"The interiors are bad, the costumes atrocious. Miss Rambova is not well dressed, nor does she film well, in the slightest degree.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Picture Play|date=May 1926|p=96|title=The Screen in Review|url=https://archive.org/stream/pictureplaymagaz24unse#page/n349/|via=The Internet Archive}} {{open access}}</ref> After its release, Rambova never worked in film, on or offscreen, again.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=234}} Three months later, Valentino died unexpectedly of [[peritonitis]], leaving Rambova inconsolable,{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=30}} and she purportedly locked herself in her bedroom for three days.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|pages=234\u20135}} Though she did not attend his funeral, she sent a [[telegram]] to Valentino's business manager George Ullman, requesting he be buried in her family crypt at [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx, New York)|Woodlawn Cemetery]] in [[the Bronx]] (a request Ullman denied).{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|pages=234\u20135}}\n\n===Writing and fashion design===\nAfter Valentino's death, Rambova relocated to New York City. There, she immersed herself in several endeavors, appearing in [[vaudeville]] at the [[Palace Theatre (New York City)|Palace Theatre]]<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Picture Play|date=May 1926|p=30|title=Over the Teacups|url=https://archive.org/stream/pictureplaymagaz24unse#page/n283/|quote=Then there's always the Palace vaudeville\u2014Natacha Rambova is making her d\u00e9but there this week.|via=Internet Archive}} {{open access}}</ref> and writing a semi-fictional play entitled ''All that Glitters'', which detailed her relationship with Valentino, and concluded in a fictionalized happy reconciliation.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=235}} She also published the 1926 memoir, ''Rudy: An Intimate Portrait by His Wife Natacha Rambova'', which contains memories of her life with him. The following year, a second memoir was published entitled ''Rudolph Valentino Recollections'' (a variation of ''Rudy: An Intimate Portrait''), in which she prefaces an addended final chapter by asking that only those \"ready to accept the truth\" read on; what follows is a detailed letter supposedly communicated by Valentino's spirit from an [[astral plane]], which Rambova claimed to have received during an automatic writing session.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|pages=245\u20136}} While residing in New York, she frequently arranged [[s\u00e9ance]]s with medium George Wehner, and claimed to have made contact with Valentino's spirit on several occasions.{{sfn|Ellenberger|2005|p=43}}{{sfn|Leider|2003|pages=407\u20138}}{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=175, 187}}{{sfn|Williams|2013|p=178}} Rambova also appeared in supporting parts in two original 1927 Broadway productions: ''Set a Thief'', a drama written by [[Edward E. Paramore, Jr.]], and ''Creoles'', a comedy written by Kenneth Perkins and Samuel Shipman.<ref name=playbill>{{cite web|work=[[Playbill]]|title=Natacha Rambova|series=Vault|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/natacha-rambova-vault-0000049689|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> \n[[File:Rambova designs in Photoplay, 1922.png|thumb|right|Costume designs by Rambova published in ''[[Photoplay]]'' in December 1922, which show her unique design sensibilities|alt=Illustrations of a man and woman in ornate costumes]]\n\nIn June 1928, she opened an elite [[Haute couture|couture]] shop on Fifth Avenue and West 55th street in Manhattan,{{sfn|Jorgensen|Scoggins|2015|p=30}} which sold Russian-inspired clothing that Rambova herself designed.{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=28}} Her clientele included Broadway and Hollywood actresses such as [[Beulah Bondi]] and [[Mae Murray]].{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=27}} On opening the shop, she commented: \"I'm in business, not exactly because I need the money, but because it enables me to give vent to an artistic urge.\"{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=27}} In addition to clothing, the shop also carried jewelry, although it is unknown if it was designed by Rambova or imported.{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|=28}} By late 1931, Rambova had grown uneasy about the economic situation of the United States during the [[Great Depression]], and feared the country would experience a drastic revolution.{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=36}} This led her close her shop and formally retire from commercial fashion design, leaving the United States to live in [[Juan-les-Pins]], France in 1932.{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=36}} On a yacht cruise to the Balearic Islands, she met her second husband \u00c1lvaro de Urz\u00e1iz, a British-educated Spanish aristocrat, whom she married in 1932.{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=36}} They lived together on the island of [[Mallorca]] and restored abandoned Spanish villas for tourists, a venture financed by Rambova's inheritance from her stepfather.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=235}}\n\nIt was during her marriage to Urz\u00e1iz that Rambova first toured Egypt in January 1936, visiting the ancient monuments in [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]], [[Luxor]], and [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]].{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=207}} While there, she met archeologist [[Howard Carter]], and became fascinated by the country and its history, which had a profound effect on her.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=231}}{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=93}} \"I felt as if I had at last returned home,\" she said. \"The first few days I was there I couldn't stop the tears streaming from my eyes. It was not sadness, but some emotional impact from the past\u2013a returning to a place once loved after too long a time.\"{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=172}} Upon returning to Spain, Urz\u00e1iz became a naval commander for the pro-fascist nationalist side during the [[Spanish Civil War]]. Rambova fled the country to a familial ch\u00e2teau in [[Nice]], where she suffered a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at age forty.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=235}} Soon after, she and Urz\u00e1iz separated. {{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=235}} Rambova remained in France until the Nazi invasion in June 1940, upon which she returned to New York.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=228}}\n\n=== Egyptology and scholarly work===\nRambova's interest in the metaphysical evolved significantly during the 1940s, and she became an avid supporter of the [[Bollingen Foundation]], through which she believed she could see a [[Past life regression|past life]] in Egypt.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=235}} Rambova was also follower of [[Helena Blavatsky]] and [[George Gurdjieff]],{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=235}} and conducted classes in her Manhattan apartment about myths, symbolism and comparative religion.{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=237}} She also began publishing articles on healing, [[astrology]], yoga, post-war rehabilitation, and numerous other topics,{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=93}}{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=35}} some of which appeared in ''American Astrology'' and ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''.<ref name=lesko/> In 1945, the Old Dominion (a predecessor to the [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation]]) awarded Rambova a grant-in-aid of [[US dollar|USD]]$500 for \"making a collection of essential cosmological symbols for a proposed archive of comparative universal symbolism.\"{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=94}} Rambova intended to use her research to generate a book, which she wanted [[Ananda Coomaraswamy]] to write, with the principal themes derived from astrology, [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophy]], and [[Atlantis]].{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=94}} In an undated letter to Mary Mellon, she wrote:\n\n{{quote|It is so necessary that gradually people be given the realization of a universal pattern of purpose and human growth, which the knowledge of the mysteries of initiation of the Atlantean past, as the source of our symbols of the Unconscious, gives ... Just as you said, knowledge of the meaning of the destruction of Atlantis and the present cycle of recurrence would give people an understanding of the present situation.{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=94}}}}\n\n[[File:Mythological Papyri title page (1957).png|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Title page of ''Mythological Papyri'' (1957)|alt=Page from a book which reads ''Mythological Papyri'' in large text]]\nRambova's intellectual investment in Egypt also led her to undertake work deciphering ancient [[Scarab (artifact)|scarabs]] and tomb inscriptions, which she began researching in 1946.<ref name=lesko/> Initially, she believed she would find evidence of a connection between ancient Egyptian belief systems and those of ancient American cultures.<ref name=lesko/> While researching at the [[Institut Fran\u00e7ais d'Arch\u00e9ologie Orientale]] in Cairo, she met the institute's director, Alexandre Piankoff, with whom she established a rapport based on their shared interest in Egyptology.{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=160}} Piankoff introduced her to his French translation of the [[Book of Caverns]], a royal funerary text, which he was working on at the time. \"To my amazement, I found that it contains all the most important esoteric material,\" Rambova wrote. \"I can only compare it to the [[Copts|Coptic]] ''[[Pistis Sophia]]'', the Tibetan ''[[The Voice of the Silence|Voice of the Silence]]'', and the Hindu [[Yoga Sutras of Patanjali|Sutras of Patanjali]]. It is what I have been looking for<!--not a mistake--> for years.\"{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=160}}\n\nHer interest in the Book of Caverns led her to abandon her studies of scarabs, and she began translating Piankoff's French translation into English, an endeavor she felt \"was the main purpose and point\" of her studies in Egypt.{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=160}} She secured a second two-year grant of US$50,000 through the Mellon and Bollingen Foundations (a considerably large grant for the time) to help Piankoff photograph and publish his work on the Book of Caverns.<ref name=lesko/> In the winter of 1949\u201350, she joined Piankoff and [[Elizabeth Thomas (Egyptologist)|Elizabeth Thomas]] in [[Luxor]] to undertake further studies.<ref name=lesko/> In the spring of 1950, the group was given permission to photograph and study inscriptions on golden shrines that had once enclosed the sarcophagus of [[Tutankhamun]], after which they toured the [[Pyramid of Unas]] at [[Saqqara]].<ref name=lesko/>\n\nAfter completing the expedition in Egypt, Rambova returned to the United States, where, in 1954, she donated her extensive collection of Egyptian artifacts (accumulated over years of research) to the [[University of Utah]]'s [[Utah Museum of Fine Arts|Museum of Fine Arts]] (UMFA).<ref>{{cite web|work=The Deseret News|title=Brief history of the Utah Museum of Fine Arts|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/844950/Brief-history-of-the-Utah-Museum-of-Fine-Arts.html|accessdate=November 10, 2017|date=May 27, 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906210146/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/844950/Brief-history-of-the-Utah-Museum-of-Fine-Arts.html|archivedate=September 6, 2015}}</ref> She settled in [[New Milford, Connecticut]], where she spent the following several years working as an editor on the first three volumes of Piankoff's series ''Egyptian Texts and Religious Representations'',{{sfn|Rambova|Pickford|2009|p=237}}<ref name=yaleschol/> which was based on the research he had done with Rambova and Thomas.<ref name=lesko/> The first volume was ''The Tomb of Ramesses VI'' published in 1954, followed by ''The Shrines of Tut-Ankh-Amon'' in 1955. During this time, she kept regular correspondence with fellow Egyptologists [[William C. Hayes]] and [[Richard Anthony Parker|Richard Parker]].<ref name=lesko/>\n\nFor the third volume of Piankoff's series, ''Mythological Papyri'' (published in 1957), Rambova contributed her own chapter in which she discussed semiotics in Egyptian [[papyrus|papyri]].<ref name=papyri>{{cite book|last1=Rambova|first1=Natacha|title=Mythological Papyri|series=Egyptian Religious Texts and Representations (Bollingen Series XL)|volume=III|editor1=Rambova, Natacha|editor2=Piankoff, Alexandre|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/PiankoffRambovaMythologicalPapyriTexts/Piankoff_Rambova_Mythological_papyri_Texts#page/n25/mode/2up|year=1957|publisher=Pantheon Books|chapter=The Symbolism of the Papyri|pages=29\u201350}}</ref> Rambova continued to write and research intensely into her sixties, often working twelve hours per day.<ref name=lesko/> In the years prior to her death, she was working on a manuscript examining texts from the Pyramid of Unas for a translation by Piankoff.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=262}} This manuscript, which exceeds a thousand pages, was donated to the Brooklyn Museum after her death.<ref name=lesko/> Two additional manuscripts were also left behind, which are part of [[Yale University]]'s Yale in Egypt collection: ''The Cosmic Circuit: Religious Origins of the Zodiac'' and ''The Mystery Pattern in Ancient Symbolism: A Philosophic Interpretation''.<ref name=yaleschol>{{cite web|work=Yale in Egypt|publisher=Yale University|url=https://egyptology.yale.edu/collections/natacha-rambova-archive-yale-university/scholarship-natacha-rambova|title=The Scholarship of Natacha Rambova|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Later life and death==\nIn the early 1950s Rambova developed [[scleroderma]], which significantly affected her throat, impeding her ability to swallow and speak.{{Sfn|Morris|1991|p=247}} She also grew delusional, believing that she was being poisoned, and quit eating, resulting in malnourishment.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=255}} On September 29, 1965, she was discovered going \"berserk\" in a hotel elevator in Manhattan.{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=255\u20136}} Rambova was admitted to [[Lenox Hill Hospital]], where she was diagnosed with paranoid psychosis brought on by malnutrition.<ref name=wfpp>{{cite web|work=Women Film Pioneers Project|publisher=Columbia University|title=Natacha Rambova|url=https://wfpp.cdrs.columbia.edu/pioneer/ccp-natacha-rambova/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224065411/https://wfpp.cdrs.columbia.edu/pioneer/ccp-natacha-rambova/|archivedate=December 24, 2015|author=Stutesman, Drake|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWith her health in rapid decline, Rambova's cousin, Ann Wollen, relocated her from her home in Connecticut to California, in order to help take care of her.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=256}} There, Rambova was admitted to Methodist Hospital in [[Arcadia, California|Arcadia]].{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=255\u20136}} On January 19, 1966 (her 69th birthday), she was relocated to a [[Nursing home care|nursing home]] at Las Encinas Hospital in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]].{{sfn|Morris|1991|pages=255\u20136}} She died there six months later of a heart attack on June 5, 1966 at the age of 69.<ref>{{cite book|title=Screen World 1967|p=239|author=Willis, John|publisher=Biblo & Tannen Publishers|year=1983|isbn=978-0-819-60308-1}}</ref>{{sfn|Ellenberger|2005|p=149}} At her wishes, Rambova was cremated, and her ashes were scattered in a forest in northern Arizona.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=228}}\n\n==Claims regarding personal life==\n[[File:Portrait of Rudolph Valentino and Natacha Rambova.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|Portrait of Valentino and Rambova, {{circa}} 1923|alt=Busts of a man and woman, both facing left]]\nClaims that Rambova was [[bisexuality|bisexual]] or homosexual date back to at least 1975 when they appeared in [[Kenneth Anger]]'s notoriously libelous ''[[Hollywood Babylon]]'', in which it is written that Rambova claimed to have never [[consummation|consummated]] her marriage with Rudolph Valentino.<ref>{{cite book|title=Hollywood Babylon|last=Anger|first=Kenneth|author-link=Kenneth Anger|p=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodbabylon00ange/page/108 108]|year=1975|publisher=Straight Arrow Books|isbn=978-0-879-32086-7|title-link=Hollywood Babylon}}</ref> This has led some historians to refer to the couple's union as a \"[[lavender marriage]].\"<ref name=norton/> The claim, however, is at odds with the grounds of Valentino's 1922 arrest after the couple's wedding: he was arrested and jailed for consummating the marriage in Palm Springs, California despite still being legally married to Jean Acker.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=114}} Discussion of Rambova's sexuality continued to appear in academic and biographical texts throughout the 1980s and beyond.{{efn|Claims that Rambova was bisexual or a lesbian arose in several academic and historical publications in the late-1980s and 1990s, including articles in the ''[[Theatre Record|London Theatre Record]]'',<ref name=london/> as well as several books, such as ''Who was that Man?: A Present for Mr. Oscar Wilde'' (1988) by [[Neil Bartlett (playwright)|Neil Bartlett]],<ref name=bartlett>{{cite book|author=Bartlett, Neil|author-link=Neil Bartlett (playwright)|title=Who was that Man?: A Present for Mr. Oscar Wilde|year=1988|p=[https://archive.org/details/whowasthatmanpre00bart/page/40 40]|publisher=Profile Books|isbn=978-1-852-42123-6|oclc=885172684|url=https://archive.org/details/whowasthatmanpre00bart/page/40}}</ref> and Dell Richards's ''Lesbian Lists: A Look at Lesbian Culture, History, and Personalities'' (1990).<ref>{{cite book|title=Lesbian Lists: A Look at Lesbian Culture, History, and Personalities|publisher=Alyson Publications|author=Richards, Dell|year=1990|p=[https://archive.org/details/lesbianlistslook00rich_0/page/176 176]|isbn=978-1-555-83163-9|oclc=21454734|url=https://archive.org/details/lesbianlistslook00rich_0/page/176}}</ref>}}\n\nThe basis of the claim is an alleged relationship Rambova had with Alla Nazimova,{{efn|\n[[Ty Burr]] notes these perceptions and rumors surrounding Rambova, Nazimova, and Valentino in his book ''Gods Like Us: On Movie Stardom and Modern Fame'' (2012),{{sfn|Burr|2012|pages=65\u20136}} and Nazimova and Rambova's alleged relationship is also written about extensively in ''The Girls: Sappho Goes to Hollywood'' (2001) by historian Diane McLellan,{{sfn|McLellan|2000|pages=56\u20139}} as well as several other books.<ref name=norton>{{cite book|last=Norton|first=Rictor|title=Myth of the Modern Homosexual: Queer History and the Search for Cultural Unity|p=57|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn= 978-1-474-28692-3|year=2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Who's who in Gay and Lesbian History: From Antiquity to World War II|editor1=Aldrich, Robert|editor2=Wotherspoon, Garry|p=57|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2001|edition=Revised|isbn=978-0-415-15983-8|oclc=813248489}}</ref>}} her friend and peer while Rambova was beginning her career in film design.{{efn|D. Michael Quinn points out the ambiguity regarding the allegations that Rambova was bisexual and had a romantic relationship with Alla Nazimova. She purportedly told friends she \"hated lesbians\" during her relationship with Valentino, which has been interpreted as both genuine and as potentially reflective of her own self-hatred and psychological denial over her sexuality.{{sfn|Quinn|2001|pages=173\u20135}} Some sources less definitively allege only her relationship with Nazimova, while others refer to her as Valentino's \"lesbian wife.\"<ref name=london>{{cite journal|journal=[[Theatre Record|London Theatre Record]]|title=Valentino: Half Moon|volume=10|issue=1\u201313|year=1990|issn=0962-1792|p=338}}</ref><ref name=bartlett/>}}{{sfn|Abrams|2008|pages=108\u20139}} Similar inferences have been made about others in Nazimova's social circle, including [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Eva Le Gallienne]], and [[Greta Garbo]].{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=246}}\n\nWhether Rambova was bisexual or homosexual is unclear; some have disputed such claims, including journalist David Wallace, who dismisses it as rumor in his 2002 book ''Lost Hollywood''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wallace|first=David|title=Lost Hollywood|page=48|publisher=Macmillan|year=2002|isbn=978-0-312-28863-1|oclc=49346768}}</ref> Biographer Morris also disputes the claim, writing in his epilogue of ''Madam Valentino'' that \"the convenient ... allegation that Rambova was a lesbian collapses when one scrutinizes the facts.\"<ref>Quoted in {{cite book|last=Anderson|first=Mark Lynn|year=2011|title=Twilight of the Idols: Hollywood and the Human Sciences in 1920s America|p=74|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-94942-3|oclc=721927339}}</ref> Additionally, a close friend of writer [[Mercedes de Acosta]] (also an alleged lover of Nazimova) told Morris that she believed Rambova and Nazimova's relationship was nothing other than platonic.{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=246}} Rambova's friend [[Dorothy Norman]] also stated that Rambova had been \"displeased\" by De Acosta's controversial 1960 autobiography, which implied she was bisexual or homosexual, as it had \"cast her in an improper light.\"{{sfn|Morris|1991|p=246}} In his 1996 book ''The Silent Feminists'', however, [[Anthony Slide]] stated that \"all who [knew] Rambova deny that she was a gay woman.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Slide|first=Anthony|year=1996|title=The Silent Feminists: America's First Women Directors|p=128| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZF44Hy1HVj4C&lpg=PA128&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=false| publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn= 978-0-810-83053-0|oclc=34190533}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural significance==\n===Design and fashion===\n[[File:Nazimova Camille 1921.jpg|thumb|right|upright=.90|Alla Nazimova in ''Camille'' (1921); Rambova's \"exotic\" set and costume designs in the film blended elements of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Nouveau]]{{sfn|Kirkham|2002|p=260}}]]\nRambova was one of the few women in Hollywood during the 1920s to serve as a head art designer in film productions.{{sfn|Kirkham|2002|p=259}} At the time, her costume and set designs were considered \"highly stylized,\" and divided opinion among critics.{{sfn|Klepper|2005|p=199}} A 1925 ''Picture Play'' magazine profile on ''[[What Price Beauty?]]'' noted the \"bizarre\" effects present, adding: \"Miss Rambova insists the picture will be popular in its appeal, and not, as one might think, \"arty.\"\"<ref name=schallert>{{cite journal|journal=Picture Play|date=August 1925|pages=46\u20137, 94|author=Schallert, Edwin|title=Natacha Rambova Emerges|url=https://archive.org/stream/pictureplaymagaz22unse#page/n671/|via=The Internet Archive}} {{open access}}</ref> Rambova's sets incorporated shimmering shades of silver and white against sharp \"''[[Modernism|moderne]]''\" lines, and blended elements of [[Bauhaus]] and Asian-inspired geometries.<ref name=stutesman/>\n\nCommenting on her career in film, design historian Robert La Vine proclaimed Rambova one of the \"most inventive designers ... ever,\" also noting her as one of few who crafted both sets and costumes.<ref name=stutesman/> Film historian Robert Klepper wrote of her designs in ''Camille'' (1921): \"In evaluating the film today, one has to give art director Natacha Rambova her due credit for her vision as an artist. The [[Art Deco|deco]] sets are beautiful, and the ultra modern design was far ahead of its time. Although Rambova may have influenced her future husband Valentino to make some bad business decisions, her talent as an artist cannot be denied.\"{{sfn|Klepper|2005|p=199}} Historian [[Pat Kirkham]] also praised her contributions to film, writing that she created \"some of the most visually unified films in Hollywood history.\"{{sfn|Kirkham|2002|p=259}} Costume historian Deborah Landis named Rambova's white rubberized tunic (worn by Alla Nazimova) and the Art Deco-inspired imagery of ''Salome'' (1922) among the \"most memorable in motion picture history.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Landis|first=Deborah|title=Dress: A Century of Hollywood Costume Design|p=[https://archive.org/details/dressedcenturyof0000land/page/32 32]|year=2007|publisher=Harper Design|isbn=978-0-060-81650-6|oclc=938099689|url=https://archive.org/details/dressedcenturyof0000land/page/32}}</ref>\n[[File:Natacha Rambova dressed by Paul Poiret.png|thumb|left|upright=0.70|Rambova {{circa}} 1926 in a dress by [[Paul Poiret]]]]\n\nThough her work in both set and costume design has been deemed influential by film and fashion historians alike,{{efn|Several fashion and textile historians have proclaimed Rambova's film and fashion design as historically relevant (including Heather Vaughn and Robert La Vine), and have noted her influence.{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|pages=27\u20139}}<ref name=stutesman>{{cite book|editor=McLean, Adrienne L.|author=Stutesman, Drake|title=Costume, Makeup, and Hair|chapter=The Silent Screen, 1895\u20131927|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=2016|isbn= 978-0-813-57153-9|p=31|oclc=972306563}}</ref>}} Rambova herself claimed to \"loathe fashion,\" adding: {{quote|I want to dress in a way that is becoming to me, whether it is the style of the hour or not. So it should be with all women, in my opinion. All women should not wear knee length skirts, even if that is the prevailing fashion; clothes that are becoming to the tall, languid type, would not do at all for a short girl of the staccato type, who has to have sharp clothes to express her personality.{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=26}}}}\n\nThus, Rambova's approach to fashion design in her post-film career was conscious of the individual, a practice which textile historian Heather Vaughn suggests was carried over from her past designing movie costumes for \"individual character types.\"{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=27}} Vaughn adds: \"While not necessarily an innovator of fashion, her Hollywood cachet and ability to synthesize fashion and traditional cultures allowed her to create designs and a personal style that continues to fascinate.\"{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=21}}\n\nRambova's clothing designs drew on various influences, described by fashion critics as blending and re-working elements of Renaissance, 18th-century, Oriental, Grecian, Russian, and Victorian fashion.{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|pages=33\u20134}}{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|pages=27\u20138}} Common preferences in her work included the [[Sleeve#Types of sleeves|dolman sleeve]], long skirts with high waists, premium velvets, and intricate embroidery,{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=27}} as well as incorporation of geometric shapes and use of \"vivid colors ... that are violent and de nite. Scarlets, vermilions, strong blues, [and] blazoning purples.\"{{sfn|Vaughn|2008|p=27}} She was cited as influential by several designers with whom she worked, including [[Norman Norell]], Adrian, and Irene Sharaff.{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=36}} Rambova typically dressed in the style of her designs, and thus her personal style was also influential: She often wore her hair in coiled \"ballerina style\" braids,{{sfn|Lambert|1997|p=233}} sometimes covered in a headscarf or [[turban]], with dangling earrings and calf-length velvet or [[brocade]] skirts.{{sfn|Leider|2012|p=47}} Actress [[Myrna Loy]] once proclaimed Rambova the \"most beautiful woman she'd ever seen.\"{{sfn|Leider|2012|p=47}} In 2003, Rambova was posthumously inducted into the Costume Designers' Guild Hall of Fame.{{sfn|Vaughn|2006|p=36}}\n\n===Scholarly influence===\nRambova's scholarly work has been regarded as significant by contemporary academics in the fields of Egyptology and history: Archaeologist Barbara Lesko notes that her contribution to Piankoff's ''Mythological Papyri'' \"demonstrates her organizational skills and her commitment to searching out truths and does not reek of unfounded theories or other eccentricity.\"<ref name=lesko/> Rambova's research, specifically her metaphysical interpretations of texts, has been deemed useful by Egyptologists Rudolph Anthes, [[Edward F. Wente|Edward Wente]], and [[Erik Hornung]].<ref name=lesko/> In the 1950s, Rambova donated her extensive collection of Egyptian artifacts to the University of Utah, displayed in the [[Utah Museum of Fine Arts]]'s Natacha Rambova Collection of Egyptian Antiquities.<ref name=lesko/>{{sfn|McGuire|1989|p=164}} Both Rambova and her mother were credited as \"vital\" to the establishment of the museum through their donations of paintings, furniture, and artifacts.<ref name=dailyu>{{cite web|work=The Daily Utah Chronicle|url=http://dailyutahchronicle.com/2016/02/16/exploring-the-legacy-of-actress-dancer-umfa-donor-natacha-rambova/|date=February 16, 2016|archivedate=December 18, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218053112/http://dailyutahchronicle.com/2016/02/16/exploring-the-legacy-of-actress-dancer-umfa-donor-natacha-rambova/|author=Ehmann, Kylee|title=Exploring the Legacy of Actress, Dancer, UMFA Donor Natacha Rambova}}</ref>\n\n==Depictions in art and film==\nRambova has been depicted across several mediums, including visual art, film, and television: She was the subject of a 1925 painting by Serbian artist [[Paja Jovanovi\u0107]] (donated by her mother to the UMFA in 1949).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://umfablog.wordpress.com/2014/02/04/collection-highlight-portrait-of-miss-winifred-de-wolfe/|work=Utah Museum of Fine Arts Blog|title=Collection Highlight: Portrait of Miss Winifred de Wolfe|date=February 4, 2014|accessdate=November 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213061039/https://umfablog.wordpress.com/2014/02/04/collection-highlight-portrait-of-miss-winifred-de-wolfe/|archivedate=February 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thekingstonfoundation.org/programs-services/art-education/art-is-100-portrait-of-natacha-rambova/|work=The Joy Kingston Foundation|title=Art is 100 at UFMA: Portrait of Natacha Rambova|accessdate=November 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217084030/http://thekingstonfoundation.org/programs-services/art-education/art-is-100-portrait-of-natacha-rambova/|archivedate=February 17, 2015}}</ref> In 1975, she was portrayed by [[Yvette Mimieux]] in [[Melville Shavelson]]'s television film ''[[The Legend of Valentino]]'' (1975),{{sfn|Ellenberger|2005|p=220}} and again by [[Michelle Phillips]] in [[Ken Russell]]'s feature film ''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'' (1977).{{sfn|Ellenberger|2005|p=221}} Ksenia Jarova later portrayed her in the American silent film ''Silent Life'' (2016), and she also figured in a fictionalized narrative in the network series ''[[American Horror Story: Hotel]]'' (2015), played by [[Alexandra Daddario]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[MTV]]|title=Alexandra Daddario Reveals How to Make 'AHS' Sex Scenes with Lady Gaga Less 'Awkward'|date=December 10, 2015|author=Murphy, Shaunna|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2685595/american-horror-story-alexandra-daddario/|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|1917\n|''[[The Woman God Forgot]]''  '''\u00a7'''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Costume designer\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=51}}\n|-\n|1920\n|''[[Why Change Your Wife?]]''  '''\u00a7'''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Costume designer\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=57}}\n|-\n|1920\n|''[[Something to Think About]]''  '''\u00a7'''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Art director, costume designer\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=57}}\n|-\n|1920\n|''[[Billions (film)|Billions]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Art director, costume designer\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}}\n|-\n|1921\n|''[[Forbidden Fruit (1921 film)|Forbidden Fruit]]''  '''\u00a7'''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Costume designer\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}}\n|-\n|1921\n|''[[Camille (1921 film)|Camille]]''  '''\u00a7'''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Art director, costume designer<br>Uncredited\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}}\n|-\n|1921\n|''Aphrodite''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Art director, costume designer (never made)\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}}\n|-\n|1922\n|''[[Beyond the Rocks]]''  '''\u00a7'''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Valentino's costumes\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}}\n|-\n|1922\n|''[[The Young Rajah]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n|Costume designer<br>Uncredited\n| align=center| {{sfn|Morris|1991|p=265}}\n|- \n|1922\n|''[[A Doll's House (