ght]]<br>[[File:Palace of Fine Arts - 2012-09-15 1840.jpg|100px|right]]A pair of standing figures, ''Contemplation'' (male)<br>and ''Wonderment'' (female), flank the relief panels<br>on each face of the Rotunda's dome.<ref name=\"Mullgardt\">{{cite book |last1=Mullgardt |first1=Louis Christian |title=The Architecture and Landscape Gardening of the Exposition \u2013 A Pictorial Survey of the Most Beautiful of the Compositions of the Panama-Pacific International Exposition |date=January 1, 1915 |publisher=Paul Elder and Company |location=San Francisco |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6oKXXGEh8UYC&pg=160#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref><br><br>The figures were recast in cast stone by Spero<br>Anargyros in 1969.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bragman |first1=Bob |title=Save the Palace of Fine Arts? In the 60s, SF wasn't so sure. |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Dramatic-Palace-of-Fine-Arts-reconstruction-11009452.php#photo-12561313 |accessdate=February 4, 2019 |publisher=San Francisco Chroncile |date=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Consolation''<ref name=\"Mullgardt\"/>{{rp|160}}<br>(''Weeping Maidens'' or ''Drooping Maidens'')\n|[[File:Weeping-Maidens-Planter-Close-Up-.jpg|100px]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Pergola of the Palace of Fine Arts,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|\n|\"In the goddesses atop the towers and minarets and in the Grecian<br>boxes adorning the Roman columns of the Palace of the Fine Arts<br>will be found the enchanting line of the [Munson's] girlish form.\"<ref name=\"Times-Dispatch\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FA8072\" |Garland figures<ref name=\"Mullgardt\"/>{{rp|162}}\n|[[File:Reliefs - Palace of Fine Arts - San Francisco, CA - DSC02454.jpg|100px]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Peristyle Walk, Palace of Fine Arts,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|\n|A set of five larger-than-life, high-relief figures, repeated around<br>the four semi-circular, ground-level planters\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[John Flanagan (sculptor)|John Flanagan]]\n|Medallion: ''Head of Audrey Munson''<ref name=\"Teall\">Gardner Teall, \"Art: The Mirror of American Genius,\" ''Hearst's Magazine'', vol. 27, no. 5 (May 1915), pp. 434\u201337.[https://books.google.com/books?id=_6wiAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA435&dq=Audrey+Munson+model&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidq6eDgb7gAhVDVd8KHZghD3M4HhDoAQhSMAk#v=onepage&q=Audrey%20Munson%20model&f=false]</ref>{{rp|435}}\n|\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Palace of Fine Arts,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|bronze\n|\n|Flanagan was awarded a PPIE Medal of Honor for his sculpture.<ref name=\"PPIE Cat\"/>{{rp|234}}\n|-\n|Medal of Award, Panama-Pacific<br>International Exposition<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/15976 Medal of Award, PPIE], from MMA.</ref>\n|[[File:Panama-Pacific medal reverse.jpg|100px]]\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |\n|bronze\n|{{cvt|2.76|in|mm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Panama-Pacific medal obverse.jpg|100px|right]]obverse:\n|-\n|rowspan=\"11\" |[[Daniel Chester French]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#BEBEBE\" |''Mourning Victory''{{efn|The early date makes it unlikely that Munson posed for the Melvin Memorial in 1906 (at age 14 or 15). Six years later, French created a mirror-image version for the Metropolitan Museum of Art, likely the ''Mourning Victory'' for which Munson posed. See [[Talk:Audrey Munson#Melvin Memorial|Talk page]] for discussion.}} \n|[[File:Mourning Victory.jpg|100px]]\n|1906\u20131908\n|Melvin Memorial,<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=Q5Y87792B9561.9161&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!16873~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Melvin&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=French,+Daniel+Chester&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 Mourning Victory], from SIRIS.</ref><br>[[Sleepy Hollow Cemetery (Concord, Massachusetts)|Sleepy Hollow Cemetery]],<br>[[Concord, Massachusetts]]\n|Tennessee marble\n|{{cvt|115|in|cm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Melvin Memorial Dedicated 16 June 1909.jpg|100px|right]]Memorial to Asa, Samuel and John Melvin,<br>three brothers who fought and died in the<br>[[American Civil War]].<ref>James C. Melvin, ''The Melvin Memorial, Sleepy Hollow Cemetery, Concord, Massachusetts, A Brother's Tribute'', (Cambridge, Massachusetts: The Riverside Press, 1910), p. xvi.[https://archive.org/details/melvinmemorialsl00roea_0/page/n23]</ref>\n|-\n|''Mourning Victory''<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15O8X848063I0.9427&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!16875~!1&ri=3&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Mourning+victory&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=French&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=3 Mourning Victory (MMA)], from SIRIS.</ref><br>(mirror image of the Melvin Memorial)<ref>Thayer Tolles, ed., ''American Sculpture in The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Vol. 1, A Catalogue of Works by Artists Born before 1865'' (MMA, 1999).</ref>{{rp|335}}\n|[[File:Mourning Victory from the Melvin Memorial MET DT11598.jpg|100px]]\n|carved<br>1912\u20131914\n|[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]],<br>Manhattan, New York City\n|marble\n|{{cvt|120.5|in|cm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Study for the Head of The Melvin Memorial MET DP225800.jpg|100px|right]]James C. Melvin, the only surviving brother,<br>funded the carving of a mirror-image marble<br>version, and donated it to MMA.<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/10912?searchField=All&amp;sortBy=relevance&amp;ft=Mourning+Victory&amp;offset=0&amp;rpp=20&amp;pos=1 Mourning Victory], from MMA.</ref><br><br>MMA also owns a bronze cast of Victory's head.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=Q5Y87792B9561.9161&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummar