een Company |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ugZDAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA242 |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref>{{rp|242}}\n|-\n|[[Ulysses Ricci]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Portrait of Miss Audrey Munson''<ref>{{cite book |title=Illustrated Catalogue: National Academy of Design, Winter Exhibition |date=January 1, 1914 |publisher=National Academy of Design |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKYVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|1914\n|whereabouts unknown\n|bronze<ref name=\"Evening World\"/>\n|\n|Exhibited at National Academy of Design in 1914<br><br>Exhibited at Syracuse Museum of Fine Arts<ref name=\"Evening World\">\"Why the Beautiful Audrey Munson Wanted Her Death Announced,\" ''The New York Evening World'', October 23, 1920, p. 11.[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030193/1920-10-23/ed-1/seq-11/]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Frederick Ruckstull]]\n|''Monument to South Carolina Women of<br>the Confederacy''<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1548W0V3592A3.1265&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!21753~!26&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Ruckstull&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 Monument to South Carolina Women of the Confederacy'] from SIRIS.</ref>\n|[[File:SC Monument to the Women of the Confederacy in Columbia IMG 4744.JPG|100px]]\n|1909\u20131912\n|[[South Carolina State House]],<br>Columbia, South Carolina\n|bronze\n|{{cvt|14|ft|m|sortable=on}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Salvatore Cartaino Scarpitta\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Lady Godiva''\n|\n|by 1914\n|unknown\n|silver\n|\n|\"Even on Fifth avenue you will find her at a famous<br>silversmith's sitting dejectedly on a white horse as Lady<br>Godiva in a beautiful piece of work made by Scarpetti {{sic}}.\"<ref name=\"El Paso\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''The Light That Failed''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 3\"/>\n|[[File:Scarpitta Light That Failed.jpg|100px]]\n|1915\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Starlight''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 3\"/>\n|\n|{{circa}}1915\n|Collection of [[John D. Rockefeller, Jr.]]<br>(1921)\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Maidenhood''<ref>Audrey Munson, \"By the 'Queen of the Artists' Studios,' Chapter 2.\" ''The Nebraska State Journal'', January 16, 1921, p. 83.</ref>\n|\n|by 1921\n|Collection of [[Henry Clay Frick]] (1921)\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Francois Tonetti\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Water Nymph''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 1\"/>\n|\n|by 1921\n|[[Kykuit]] (John D. Rockefeller Estate)<br>Pocantico Hills, New York\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Edgar Walter\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FA8072\" |''Beauty and the Beast''\n|[[File:Edgar Walter - La belle et la bete.jpg|100px]]\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Beauty and the Beast Fountain,<br>Court of Flowers,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|staff\n|\n|[[File:B&B Todd Story of Expo vol.1 opp. p.234.jpg|100px|right]]Beauty and the Beast Fountain:\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" |[[Adolph Alexander Weinman]]\n|''Day'' and ''Night''<br><br>Pair of figures flanking the exterior clocks,<br>repeated over the station's four main<br>entrances.<br><br>The station was demolished, 1963-1966.\n|[[File:The New York improvement and tunnel extension of the Pennsylvania railroad. Issued October, 1910 (1910) (14759502262).jpg|100px]]<br>[[File:Pennsylvania Station aerial view, 1910s.jpg|100px]]<br>[[File:Penn Station demolition, June 25, 1966.jpg|100px]]\n|{{circa}}1910\n|[[Pennsylvania Station (1910)|Pennsylvania Station]],<br>(bordered by 31st Street, 7th Avenue,<br>33rd Street and 8th Avenue),<br>Manhattan, New York City\n|pink granite\n|{{cvt|10|ft|m|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Night, from Pennsylvania Station, by Weinman, at Brooklyn Museum, NY.jpg|100px|right]]Weinman's figures of ''Day'' and ''Night'' flanked the<br>clocks over the station's 7th and 8th Avenue main<br>entrances, and were repeated over the 31st and<br>33rd Street entrances.<br><br>A salvaged figure of ''Night'' was donated to the<br>Brooklyn Museum in 1966.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1VV1200O41231.38135&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!300860~!6&ri=5&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Weinman&index=.AW&uindex=&oper=&term=Night&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=5 Night], from SIRIS.</ref><br><br>[[File:Eagle Scout Memorial Fountain Kansas City MO.jpg|100px|right]]A complete clock entablature decorates the ''Eagle<br>Scout Memorial Fountain'' in Kansas City, Missouri.<br><br>Another clock entablature (disassembled) is at<br>[[Ringwood State Park]] in Passiac County, New<br>Jersey.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=155120448M1R8.39689&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!338533~!8&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Weinman&index=.AW&uindex=&oper=&term=night&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 \"Day and Night\" Clock Entablature], from SIRIS.</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''[[Manhattan Municipal Building#Pinnacle|Civic Fame]]''<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15K89019L41P6.1276&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!5808~!16&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=civic&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Weinman&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 Civic Fame], from SIRIS.</ref><ref name=\"Munson Chapter 7\">Audrey Munson, \"By the 'Queen of the Artists' Studios,' Chapter 7.\" ''The Washington Times'', February 20, 1921, p. 83.</ref>\n|[[File:Civic Fame.jpg|100px]]\n|1913\n|atop [[Manhattan Municipal Building]],<br>Centre Street at Chambers Street,<br>Manhattan, New York City\n|gilded bronze\n|{{cvt|25|ft|m|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Manhattan Municipal Building by David Shankbone edited-1 crop.jpg|100px|right]]Manhattan Municipal Building:\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Descending Night''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 1\">Audrey Munson, \"By the 'Queen of the Artists' Studios,' Chapter 1.\" ''The San Francisco Examiner'', January 9, 1921, p. 83.</ref><br>atop column\n|[[File:DescendingNightAAW.jpg|100px]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |1915\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Fountain of the Setting Sun,<br>Court of the Universe,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|rowspan=\"2\" |staff\n|\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[File:The story of the exposition; being the official history of the international celebration held at San Francisco in 1915 to commemorate the discovery of the Pacific Ocean and the construction of the (14579801637).jpg|100px|right]]Fountain of the Setting Sun (at left):\n|-\n|''Goddess of Truth''<br>at base of column\n|[[File:FountainoftheSetting SunAAW.jpg|100px]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Walking Liberty Half Dollar]]\n|[[File:1916-S 50C (obv).jpg|100px]]\n|1916\n|\n|90% silver<br>10% copper\n||{{cvt|1.203|in|mm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:1943D Mercury Dime obverse.jpg|100px|right]]Munson also may have been Weinman's model for<br>the [[Mercury dime]] (1916).\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Daphnis and Chloe''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 5\">Audrey Munson, \"By the 'Queen of the Artists' Studios,' Chapter 5.\" ''The Washington Times'', February 6, 1921, p. 83.</ref>{{efn|This direct claim made over Munson's name in the 5th of her 20 articles is not consistent with the declining fortunes of the [[Devonshire House]] circa World War I, nor with [https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/adolph-weinman-papers-9338/series-1/reel-5884-frames-12-33 Weinman's exhaustive C.V.], which shows no work at all outside the United States}}\n|\n|by 1921\n|[[Devonshire House]], (prior to 1921)<br>London, England\n|\n|\n|as [[Daphnis and Chloe|Chloe]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Paganism Immortal''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 6\"/>\n|[[File:Whitney Paganism SAAM-J0074484.jpg|100px]]\n|{{circa}}1910\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Fountain of El Dorado''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 6\"/>\n|[[File:Artincalifornias00port 0588.jpg|100px]]<br><br>[[File:Whitney Door to El Dorado hi res SAAM-S0002530.jpg|100px]]\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Tower of Jewels Arcade,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|\n|\n|Whitney was awarded a PPIE bronze medal for her sculpture.<ref name=\"PPIE Cat\"/>{{rp|248}}<br><br>[[File:Whitney friezes Perry p.45.jpg|100px|right]]\"[Munson] mingles, many times over, in the crowd<br>pressing forward toward the mysterious portal of<br>Mrs. Harry Payne Whitney's ''Fountain of El<br>Dorado''.\"<ref>\"Audrey Munson, the 'Exposition Girl',\" ''Sunset Magazine'', vol. 35, no. 1 (July 1915), p. 164.[https://books.google.com/books?id=UGwpAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA164&dq=whitney+audrey+munson&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDxPTbl9jgAhUGtlkKHTE9DhQQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=whitney%20audrey%20munson&f=false]</ref>\n|-\n|Bruno Louis Zimm \n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FA8072\" |Relief panels:<br>''The Triumph of the Arts''<br>''The Struggle for the Beautiful''<br>''The Power of the Arts''<ref>Frank Morton Todd, ''The Story of the Exposition, Volume 2'' (New York and London: G. P. Putnam's Sons, 1921), p. 319.</ref>\n|[[File:Zimm PPIE Rotunda panels Burness p.53.jpg|100px]]\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Attic of Rotunda,<br>Palace of Fine Arts,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|staff\n|{{cvt|14|ft|m|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Palace of Fine Arts - March 2018 (1539).jpg|100px|right]][[File:San Francisco Palace of Fine Arts - with Trees 02.jpg|right|100px]]''Truth'' is the nude female figure at the center of<br>''The Struggle for the Beautiful''.\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Audrey Munson \"Purity\" spot illustration.jpg|center|thumb|630px|Thumbnail sketches of Munson in the poses of famous works of art, 1916 newspaper ad for ''Purity''. Munson was<br>the model for Karl Bitter's ''Pomona'' (3rd from left) and Adolph Alexander Weinman's ''Descending Night'' (center).<ref name=\"MPW\"/>]]\n\nAll four films in which Munson appeared were thought to have been [[Lost film|lost]], until a copy of ''Purity'' (1916) was recovered in France in 2009.<ref name=\"Silent Era\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/P/Purity1916.html |title=Purity |website=The Progressive Silent Film List |publisher=Silent Era |access-date=January 23, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Audrey Munson1.jpg|right|thumb|240px|Audrey Munson and [[Thomas A. Curran]] in ''[[Inspiration (1915 film)|Inspiration]]'' (1915), her film debut]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1915\n| ''[[Inspiration (1915 film)|Inspiration]]''\n| The Model\n| Reissued as ''The Perfect Model'' (1918)<ref name=\"Thanhouser\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thanhouser.org/tcocd/Filmography_files/ind2t6i9o.htm |title=Inspiration |last1=Bowers |first1=Q. David |website=Thanhouser Films: An Encyclopedia and History |publisher=Thanhouser Company Film Preservation, Inc. |access-date=January 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208052042/http://www.thanhouser.org/tcocd/Filmography_files/ind2t6i9o.htm |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&TBL=PN&Type=CA&ID=16783|title=Audrey Munson |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |access-date=January 23, 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 1916\n| ''[[Purity (film)|Purity]]''\n| Purity / Virtue\n|<ref name=\"AFI\"/> \n|-\n| 1916\n| ''The Girl o' Dreams''\n| Norma Hansen\n|<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|-\n| 1921\n| ''[[Heedless Moths]]''\n| Audrey Munson\n| Based on Munson's stories and articles for ''Hearst's Sunday Magazine''<ref name=\"AFI\"/>\n|}\n\nIn 2010, film director Roberto Serrini made a documentary<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cineclast.com/2016/03/06/audrey-munson-the-tragic-1st-supermodel/|title=Audrey Munson. The 1st Supermodel.|date=2016-03-06|website=GOING AGAINST THE GRAIN IN FILM, FOOD, & FOREIGN PLACES.|language=en|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> about Munson which was featured in several news outlets including the ''New York Post''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/03/05/nycs-first-supermodel-died-alone-in-an-insane-asylum/|title=NYC\u2019s first supermodel died alone in an insane asylum|last=Tucker|first=Reed|date=2016-03-05|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n===Informational notes===\n{{Noteslist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Bone, James (2016) ''The Curse of Beauty: The Scandalous & Tragic Life of Audrey Munson, America's First Supermodel''. New York: Regan Arts. {{ISBN|978-1942872030}}\n*Donnelly, Elisabeth (Summer 2015) \"[http://www.believermag.com/issues/201508/?read=article_donnelly Descending Night]\", ''[[The Believer (magazine)|The Believer]]'', v.13 n.2.\n*[[Louis Christian Mullgardt|Mullgardt, Louis Christian]] (1915) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=jF0AAAAAYAAJ& The Architecture and Landscape Gardening of the Exposition \u2013 A Pictorial Survey of the Most Beautiful of the Compositions of the Panama-Pacific International Exposition]''. San Francisco: Paul Elder and Company.\n*Neuhaus, Eugen (1915) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=DB0WpvnZomIC& The Art of the Exposition \u2013 Personal Impressions of the Architecture, Sculpture, Mural Decorations, Color Scheme & Other Aesthetic Aspects of the Panama-Pacific International Exposition]''. San Francisco: Paul Elder and Company.\n*Rozas, Diane & Gottehrer, Anita Bourne (1999) ''American Venus: The Extraordinary Life of Audrey Munson, Model and Muse''. Los Angeles: Balcony Press. {{ISBN|1-890449-04-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Audrey Munson}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0613242|name=Audrey Munson}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://jschumacher.typepad.com/audrey_munson/ Blog devoted to Munson in NYC]\n* [http://www.andreageyer.info/projects/audrey_munson/munsonmain.htm The Audrey Munson Project]\n* [http://digitalcollections.lib.washington.edu/cdm/singleitem/collection/sayre/id/7157/rec/1 Audrey Munson], J. Willis Sayre Photographs Collection, University of Washington\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/09/nyregion/thecity/09muns.html Portrait photo, 1922], ''The New York Times'', December 9, 2007\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-36420700 \"America's first supermodel\"], BBC News, May 31, 2016; video with images: photos, film, sculpture\n* [https://99percentinvisible.org/episode/miss-manhattan/ \"Miss Manhattan\"], 99% invisible, February 15, 2016, Podcast, video, images.\n\n{{Karl Bitter}}\n{{Alexander Stirling Calder}}\n{{Daniel Chester French|state=collapsed}}\n{{Adolph Weinman}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munson, Audrey}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American artists' models]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American child models]]\n[[Category:Female models from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Rochester, New York]]\n[[Category:Nude art]]\n[[Category:Nudity]]\n[[Category:People with mood disorders]]\n[[Category:People with schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n[[Category:Muses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|20th-century American artist's model and film actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Audrey Munson\n| image                     = Munson, Audrey, Miss, with Buzzer the cat, portrait photograph.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = with Buzzer the cat (1915)\n| birth_name                = Audrey Marie Munson\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date|1891|6|8|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Rochester, New York]], US\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1996|2|20|1891|6|8|mf=yes}}\n| death_place               = [[Ogdensburg, New York]], US\n| death_cause               = \n| resting_place             = New Haven Cemetery \n| nationality               = American\n| occupation                = Artist's model, actress\n| years_active              = 1906\u20131921\n}}\n\n'''Audrey Marie Munson''' (June 8, 1891 \u2013 February 20, 1996) was an American [[model (person)|artist's model]] and film actress, today considered \"America's First Supermodel.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\">{{Cite book|first=James|last=Bone|title=The Curse of Beauty: The Scandalous and Tragic Life of Audrey Munson, America's First Supermodel|publisher=ReganArts|location=New York City|date=2016|isbn=|pages=}}</ref> In her time, she was variously known as \"'''Miss Manhattan'''\", the \"'''Panama\u2013Pacific Girl'''\", the \"'''Exposition Girl'''\" and \"'''American Venus'''.\" She was the model or inspiration for more than twelve statues in [[New York City]], and many others elsewhere. Munson was also the first American actress to appear fully nude in film, in ''[[Inspiration (1915 film)|Inspiration]]'' (1915), the first of her four [[silent film]]s.<ref name=gilding />\n\n== Career ==\n\n{{quotation|Long after she and everyone else of this generation shall have become dust, Audrey Munson, who posed for three-fifths of all the statuary of the Panama\u2013Pacific exposition, will live in the bronzes and canvasses of the art centers of the world.|''Richmond (Virginia) Times-Dispatch'', August 1, 1915<ref name=\"Times-Dispatch\">{{cite news |title=Millions Will View Her Classic Features |url=https://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=RTD19150801.1.31&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN------- |accessdate=8 February 2019 |publisher=Richmond (Virginia) Times-Dispatch |date=1 August 1915 }}</ref> }}\n\n[[File:Sunset-FC-October-1915.jpg|left|thumb|[[Adolph Alexander Weinman]]'s ''Descending Night'', featured on the cover of ''[[Sunset (magazine)|Sunset]]'' magazine (October 1915)<ref name=\"Rozas and Bourne-Gotteher\"/>]]\n\n=== Model ===\n\nAudrey Marie Munson was born in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]], on June 8, 1891,<ref name=\"audrey\">{{cite web |title=Rediscovering Audrey |first= Justin D. |last=White |url= http://www.andreageyer.info/projects/audrey_munson/munson_book/MunsonPages/PDF/JustinWhite.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Andreageyer.info}}</ref><ref name=\"Rozas and Bourne-Gotteher\"/>{{rp|12}} to Edgar Munson and Katherine \"Kittie\" Mahaney.  Her father was from [[Mexico (town), New York|Mexico, New York]], and she later lived there. Her parents divorced when she was eight, and Audrey and her mother moved to [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"db\">{{cite web | last = Bone | first = James | title =The Glamorous Life And Tragic Fall of America's First Supermodel | url = http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/04/24/the-glamorous-life-and-tragic-fall-of-america-s-first-supermodel.html | website =[[The Daily Beast]]  | date = April 23, 2016 | access-date = April 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909 the pair moved to New York City, where the 17-year-old Audrey sought a career as an actress and chorus girl.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> Her first role on Broadway was as a \"footman\" in ''The Boy and The Girl'' at the Aerial Gardens of the [[New Amsterdam Theatre]], which ran from May 31 \u2013 June 19, 1909.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/Person/View/409405|title=Internet Broadway Database|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> She also appeared in ''The Girl and the Wizard'', ''Girlies'' and ''La Belle Paree''.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n[[File:2008-05-04 CanonS3 IMG 3076 Civic Fame crop.jpg|thumb|190px|Adolph Alexander Weinman's ''Civic Fame'' (1913), atop the Manhattan Municipal Building, New York City]]\nWhile window-shopping on Fifth Avenue with her mother she was spotted by photographer [[Felix Benedict Herzog]], who asked her to pose for him at his studio in the [[Lincoln Arcade]] Building on Broadway and 65th Street.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> Herzog introduced her to his friends in the art world. She posed for muralist [[William de Leftwich Dodge]], who gave her a letter of introduction to [[Isidore Konti]].  Konti was her first sculptor, and her first nude modeling.<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 1\"/>  From this point Munson would pose for a few well-known visual artists, including painter [[Francis Coates Jones]], illustrators [[Harrison Fisher]], Archie Gunn, and [[Charles Dana Gibson]],<ref name=\"El Paso\"/> and photographers Herzog and [[Arnold Genthe]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/>{{rp|29, 43}} but she was predominantly a sculptors' model.\n\nMunson's first acknowledged credit is Konti's marble statuary called ''Three Graces'' unveiled in the new Grand Ballroom at the [[Hotel Astor]] in Times Square in September 1909.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> She posed for all three graces.  Soon after, and for the next decade, Munson became the model of choice for the first tier of American sculptors, posing for a long list of freestanding statuary, monuments, and allegorical architectural sculpture on state capitols and other major public buildings.  According to ''[[The Sun (New York)|The Sun]]'' in 1913, \"Over a hundred artists agree that if the name of Miss Manhattan belongs to anyone in particular it is to this young woman.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Andrew |title=Rescuing a Heroine From the Clutches of Obscurity|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/04/14/nyregion/neighborhood-report-new-york-up-close-rescuing-heroine-clutches-obscurity.html|accessdate=April 9, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=April 14, 1996}}</ref>  By 1915, she was so well established that she became [[Alexander Stirling Calder]]'s model of choice, when he became Director of Sculpture for the [[Panama\u2013Pacific International Exposition]] held in San Francisco that year. Her figure was \"ninety times repeated against the sky\" on one building alone, atop the colonnades of the Court of the Universe, roughly modeled on [[St. Peter's Square]] in the Vatican.<ref>{{cite book |last1=James |first1=Juliet Helena Lumbard |title=Palaces and Courts of the Exposition: A Handbook of the Architecture, Sculpture and Mural Paintings with Special Reference to the Symbolism |date=1 January 1915 |publisher=California Book Company |pages=47-49 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MjAaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47 |accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref> In fact, Munson posed for three-fifths of the sculpture created for the event<ref name=\"Times-Dispatch\" /> and earned fame as the \"Panama\u2013Pacific Girl\".<ref name=\"P-P Girl\" >{{cite news |last= |first= |date=June 27, 1915|title=The Broad Minded Romance of the Famous Panama-Pacific Girl |url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=RTD19150627.1.50 |newspaper=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]] |access-date=January 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Film actress ===\n\nMunson's newfound celebrity helped launch her career in the nascent film industry and she starred in four silent films. In the first, ''[[Inspiration (1915 film)|Inspiration]]'' (1915), the story of a sculptor's model, she appeared [[nude scene|fully nude]], the first woman to do so in an American motion picture. The censors were reluctant to ban the film, fearing they would also have to ban [[Renaissance art]]. Munson's films were a [[box office]] success, although the critics were divided.<ref name=\"Rozas and Bourne-Gotteher\">{{cite book| author=Rozas and Bourne-Gottehrer| title=American Venus: The Extraordinary Life of Audrey Munson, Model and Muse| publisher= Balcony Press|location= Los Angeles|date=1999}}</ref>{{rp|81\u201382}} The studio hired a lookalike named Jane Thomas to do Munson's acting scenes, while Munson did the scenes where she posed nude.<ref>{{cite news|last=Donnelly |first=Elisabeth |url= http://www.believermag.com/issues/201508/?read=article_donnelly |title= Descending Night |work=[[The Believer (magazine)|The Believer]] | volume= 13 |issue=2 |date= Summer 2015 |accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref> Her second film, ''Purity'' (1916), made in Santa Barbara, California, is the only one of her films to survive, being rediscovered in 1993 in a \"pornography\" collection in France and acquired by the French national cinema archive.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> Her third film, ''The Girl o' Dreams'', also made in Santa Barbara, was completed by the fall of 1916 and copyrighted on December 31, 1918, but appears never to have been released.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/>\n\nMunson returned to the East Coast by train via Syracuse in December 1916, having been involved with high society in New York and Newport, Rhode Island. There are accounts where her mother insists she married the son of a \"Comstock Lode\" silver heir,  [[Hermann_Oelrichs#Personal_life|Hermann Oelrichs Jr.]], then the richest bachelor in America. There is no record of this. On January 27, 1919, she wrote a rambling letter to the US State Department denouncing Oelrichs as part of a pro-German network that had driven her out of the movie business. She said she planned to abandon the United States to restart her movie career in England.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fold3.com/image/3621646/|title=Fold3.com FBI archive \"Old German Case Files\"|last=|first=|date=1919|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Notoriety ===\n\n[[File:Nude Audrey Munson - Heedless Moths.jpg|thumb|left|in ''[[Heedless Moths]]'' (1921)]]\n\nIn 1919 Audrey Munson was living with her mother in a boarding house at 164 West 65th Street, Manhattan, owned by Dr. Walter Wilkins. Wilkins fell in love with Munson, and on February 27 murdered his wife, Julia, so he could be available for marriage.<ref name=\"gilding\" /> Munson and her mother left New York, and the police sought them for questioning. After a nationwide hunt, they were located. They refused to return to New York, but were questioned by agents from the [[William J. Burns International Detective Agency|Burns Detective Agency]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada. The contents of the affidavits they supplied have never been revealed, but Audrey Munson strongly denied she had any romantic relationship with Dr. Wilkins.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> Wilkins was tried, found guilty, and sentenced to the [[electric chair]]. He hanged himself in his prison cell before the sentence could be carried out.<ref name=\"obscurity\">{{cite web|url=http://keithyorkcity.wordpress.com/2012/10/25/audrey-munson-miss-manhattan-died-in-obscurity-in-1996/ |title=Audrey Munson: \"Miss Manhattan\" Died in Obscurity in 1996 &#124; Keith York City |publisher=Keithyorkcity.wordpress.com |date= |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs a direct consequence or not, the Wilkins killing marked the end of Munson's ten-year modeling career.  She continued to seek regular newspaper coverage.  By 1920 Munson, unable to find work anywhere, was reported as living in [[Syracuse, New York]], supported by her mother, who sold kitchen utensils door to door.  In November 1920 she was said to be working as a ticket-taker in a dime museum.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Locan |first1=Clarence A. |title=Audrey Munson, Whose \"Perfect Form\" Was the Rage Here in 1915, Destitute in East |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/27404418/?terms=audrey%2Bmunson%2Barrested |accessdate=February 3, 2019 |publisher=San Francisco Chronicle |date=November 7, 1920}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Some sculptural features of the Panama-Pacific Exposition.jpg|thumb|Munson posed for all these Panama-Pacific International Exhibition sculptures.]]\n\nFrom January through May 1921 a series of twenty serialized articles ran in ''[[The American Weekly|Hearst's Sunday Magazine]]'' in dozens of Sunday newspaper supplements,<ref name=\"AFI\" /><ref name=\"Thanhouser\" /> under Munson's name, the whole series entitled ''By the 'Queen of the Artists' Studios'. ''  The twenty articles relate anecdotes from her career, with warnings about the fates of other models.  In one she asked the reader to imagine her future:<ref name=\"gilding\" />\n\n{{Quote|What becomes of the artists' models? I am wondering if many of my readers have not stood before a masterpiece of lovely sculpture or a remarkable painting of a young girl, her very abandonment of draperies accentuating rather than diminishing her modesty and purity, and asked themselves the question, \"Where is she now, this model who was so beautiful?\"}}\n\nIn February that year, agent-producer Allen Rock took out advertisements showing a $27,500 check he said he had paid Munson to star in a fourth film titled ''[[Heedless Moths]]'' based on these writings. She later said the $27,500 check was just a \"publicity stunt,\" and she filed suit against Allen Rock.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> Those proceedings revealed that the twenty articles had been ghostwritten by journalist Henry Leyford Gates.<ref>{{cite news |title=Journalist Finds New Material on Genocide Survivor Film Star Aurora Mardiganian |url=https://mirrorspectator.com/2016/05/19/journalist-finds-new-material-on-genocide-survivor-film-star-aurora-mardiganian/ |accessdate=February 16, 2019 |publisher=Armenian Spectator-Review |date=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1921 Munson conducted a nationwide search, carried by the United Press, for the perfect man to marry.  She ended the search in August claiming she didn't want to get married anyway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Audrey Munson Retreats in Face of Concerted Drive by Many \"Perfect\" Men |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/326634865/?terms=audrey%2Bmunson%2Barrested |accessdate=February 3, 2019 |publisher=Buffalo Enquirer |date=August 19, 1921}}</ref> On October 3, 1921 she was arrested at the Royal Theater (later the Towne Theater) in St. Louis on a morals charge related to her personal appearance with [[Purity_(film)#\"Innocence\"|the film ''Innocence'']], in which she had a leading role.<ref>{{cite news |title=Audrey Munson Pinched for Posing, Tells View of Silk-Shinned Immorality |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/69803485/?terms=audrey%2Bmunson%2Binnocence%2Bfilm |accessdate=February 3, 2019 |publisher=Belvidere (Illinois) Daily Republican |date=October 4, 1921}}</ref> She and her manager, independent film producer Ben Judell,<ref>later of [[Producers Releasing Corporation]]</ref> were both acquitted.  Weeks later she was still appearing in St. Louis, along with screenings of ''Innocence'', enacting \"a series of new poses from famous paintings\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Innocence ad |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/204516158/?terms=audrey%2Bmunson%2Binnocence |accessdate=February 3, 2019 |issue=October 27, 1921 |publisher=St. Louis Star and Times}}</ref>\n\nOn May 27, 1922, Munson attempted suicide by swallowing a solution of [[bichloride of mercury]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |author2= |title=Model Who Attempted Suicide by Poison Will Recover |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/05/29/archives/audrey-munson-is-out-of-danger-model-who-attempted-suicide-by.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 29, 1922 |accessdate=February 4, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Final years ===\nOn June 8, 1931, her mother petitioned a judge to commit her to a [[lunatic asylum]]. The Oswego County judge ordered Munson be admitted into a psychiatric facility for treatment. She remained in the [[Ogdensburg Correctional Facility|St. Lawrence State Hospital for the Insane]] in [[Ogdensburg, New York|Ogdensburg]], where she was treated for [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] and [[schizophrenia]], for 65 years, until her death at the age of 104.<ref name=gilding>{{cite news |first=Saki |last=Knafo |title=The Girl Beneath the Gilding  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/09/nyregion/thecity/09muns.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 9, 2007 |accessdate=February 4, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Brock, Chris|url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20140919/CURR/140918631|title=\u2018American Muse\u2019 story of beauty from Oswego County carved in stone, forgotten in memory|newspaper=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|date=September 19, 2014|access-date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202034713/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20140919/CURR/140918631|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1950s Munson was sufficiently famous to serve as the subject of an anecdote in a memoir that [[P.G. Wodehouse]] and [[Guy Bolton]] wrote of their years on Broadway, ''[[Bring on the Girls!]]'' (1953), though that memoir is considered more fiction than fact by Wodehouse's biographer.<ref>{{cite book|last=Donaldson |first= Frances |title=P.G. Wodehouse: The Authorized Biography |publisher=Futura |location =London | date=1983 |isbn= 0-7088-2356-4 | page=12}}</ref>{{efn|A letter to ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 1996 recounted the story:<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weller|first1=Steve|title=Famed Artist's Model Bared All for a Playwright |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/06/16/nyregion/l-famed-artist-s-model-bared-all-for-a-playwright-023604.html|accessdate=April 9, 2016| work=The New York Times|date=June 16, 1996}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Wodehouse was working alone in an apartment that has recently been vacated by a sculptor. His wife told him to expect a woman who would redo the couch, so when Audrey Munson knocked and asked if there was any work for her, Wodehouse said yes and \"How much would it be altogether?\"\n\n\"You want the altogether?\" she replied and ducked into a bedroom. She \"emerged in an advanced form of nudity,\" which Wodehouse thought was \"pretty eccentric even for a lady decorator.\"\n\nAnyway, things got sorted out, and Bolton thought the situation so funny that he incorporated it into the play they were working on, ''Oh, Lady, Lady''.}}}}\n\nFor decades she had no visitors at the asylum, but she was rediscovered there by a half-niece, Darlene Bradley, in 1984, when Munson was 93.<ref name=\"autogenerated2016\"/> Munson died February 20, 1996, at the age of 104.<ref>Number: ''082-42-0284''; Issue State: ''New York''; Issue Date: ''1996''. Ancestry.com. ''U.S., Social Security Death Index, 1935\u20132014'' [database on-line]. Provo, UT: USA: Ancestry.com Operations, Inc., 2011.</ref> She was buried without a gravestone of her own in the Munson family plot in New Haven Cemetery, [[New Haven, New York]]. In 2016, 20 years after her death, her family decided to add a simple tombstone for what would have been her 125th birthday.<ref>{{Find a Grave|grid=15080347|name=Audrey Marie Munson| accessdate= May 26, 2016|date=July 29, 2006}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Sculptures of Munson==\n\nThe entries below are mentioned in at least one credible source.  Coverage of Munson's career, and the works attributed to her modelling work, contained inaccuracies during her lifetime, some of which have been perpetuated more recently.  Munson herself was inconsistent about her age and other matters.  For instance, a June 1915 article listed the 24-year-old Munson's age as 18,<ref name=\"P-P Girl\" /> and an August 1915 press release claimed that she'd started posing at age 14.<ref name=\"Times-Dispatch\" /> The latter would have been four years prior to her first admitted modeling credit, Konti's ''Three Graces'' group at the Hotel Astor, unveiled to the public in September 1909 (when she was 18).\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" |'''Key:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#BEBEBE\" |Attributed works for which Munson<br>was too young to have posed\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |Works for which Munson<br>confirmed she posed\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FA8072\" |Works attributed to Munson,<br>but without direct evidence\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Panama-Pacific<br>International Exposition\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Sculptor\n! Title\n! Image\n! Year\n! Location/GPS Coordinates\n! Material\n! Height\n! Notes\n|- \n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[Herbert Adams (sculptor)|Herbert Adams]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''The Three Graces''<ref name=\"El Paso\">\"The 'Most Copied' Girl in America,\" ''The El Paso Times'', March 22, 1914, p. 48.</ref>\n|[[File:Adams McMillan Fountain ALNY 1911.jpg|100px]]\n|1912\n|[[McMillan Fountain|James McMillan Fountain]],<br>[[McMillan Reservoir]],<br>Washington, D.C. \n|bronze\n|{{cvt|12|ft|m|sortable=on}}<br>(overall)\n|[[File:McMillan Fountain.jpg|100px|right]]The McMillan Fountain was disassembled for the<br>1941 expansion of McMillan Reservoir. The<br>pieces spent decades in storage, and suffered<br>vandalism. Only the central figures and upper<br>basin remain.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!359968~!0#focus McMillan Fountain], from SIRIS.</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Priestess of Culture''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 7\"/>\n|[[File:Perry The Sculpture & Murals of the PPIE p.74.jpg|100px]] \n|1914\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Rotunda, Palace of Fine Arts,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|[[Staff (building material)|staff]]\n|{{cvt|51.5|in|cm|sortable=on}}\n|Adams was awarded a PPIE Medal of Honor for his sculpture.<ref name=\"PPIE Cat\"/>{{rp|229}}<br><br>