EB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|The Elements: ''Air''\n|[[File:Perry Air The Sculpture & Murals of the PPIE p.24.jpg|100px]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |1915\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Flanking stairs to sunken garden,<br>Court of the Universe,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|rowspan=\"2\" |staff\n|rowspan=\"2\" |\n|rowspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n|The Elements: ''Earth''\n|[[File:Perry Earth The Sculpture & Murals of the PPIE p.24.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|''Fountain of the Earth''\n|[[File:Aitken Fountain of Earth 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition.jpg|100px]]\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Court of the Universe,<br>Panama-Pacific International Exposition\n|staff\n|\n|[[File:Perry Fountain of Earth sculpturemuralso00panarich 0055.jpg|100px|right]][[File:-Pan-Pacific International Exposition- MET DP170681.jpg|100px|right]]Fountain of the Earth: \n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\" |[[Karl Bitter]]\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#BEBEBE\" |''Venus'' \n|[[File:Karl Bitter at Work.jpg|100px]]\n|{{circa}}1895\n|Library,<br>[[Biltmore Estate]],<br>Asheville, North Carolina\n|steel\n|\n|Bitter modeled a ''Venus'' statuette as an andiron figure for Biltmore<br>in the 1890s.{{efn|Bitter modeled a statuette of ''Venus'' as the crowning figure for an andiron in the library of the [[Biltmore Estate]] in Asheville, North Carolina, 1893\u20131895.<ref>Wayne Craven, ''Gilded Mansions: Grand Architecture and High Society'' (W. W. Norton & Company, 2009), p. 203.</ref> He exhibited a plaster version at the National Sculpture Society in 1898,<ref name=\"Dearinger\"/> and donated a {{cvt|23.75|in|cm|sortable=on}} bronze cast to the [[National Academy of Design]] in May 1904.<ref name=\"Dearinger\">David B. Dearinger, ''Paintings & Sculpture at the National Academy of Design, Volume 1: 1826\u20131925'' (Hudson Hills Press, 2004), p. 44.</ref>}}<br><br>A life-sided ''Venus Coming from the Bath'' was photographed in<br>Bitter's studio in 1901.<ref>''National Magazine'', vol. 13, no. 6 (March 1901) (Boston: Joe Mitchell Chapple), p. 491.[https://books.google.com/books?id=9o7NAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA491&dq=Karl+Bitter+Venus&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwipjvfAqaLgAhUG2FkKHeunDk0Q6AEIPDAE#v=onepage&q=Karl%20Bitter%20Venus&f=false]</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Venus de Milo'' (with arms)\n|\n|by 1921\n|[[Noordeinde Palace]],<br>[[The Hague]], Netherlands\n|marble\n|\n|[[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands]] commissioned a ''Venus de<br>Milo'' (with arms) from Bitter. Munson wrote that Bitter experimented<br>with different arrangements of the arms, modeled the sculpture in<br>clay, and carved it in marble himself.<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 4\">Audrey Munson, \"By the 'Queen of the Artists' Studios,' Chapter 4.\" ''The San Francisco Examiner'', January 30, 1921, p. 80.</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#BEBEBE\" |''Peace''<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=154972YD8968D.4804&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!7106~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=peace&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Bitter,+Karl&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 Peace], from SIRIS.</ref>\n|[[File:2016 Appellate courthouse Karl Bitter Peace.jpg|100px]]\n|1896\u20131900\n|[[Appellate Division Courthouse of New York State|Appellate Division Courthouse of]]<br>New York State,<br>35 East 25th Street,<br>Manhattan, New York City\n|\n|\n|Bitter completed his work on the Appellate Courthouse in June<br>1899,<ref>Dennis, James M., ''Karl Bitter: Architectural Sculptor 1867\u20131915'', University of Wisconsin Press, Madison, 1967, p. 71.</ref> about the time Munson turned 8 years old.\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Peace''\n|[[File:Audrey Munson & Karl Bitter.jpg|100px]]\n|by 1921\n|\n|\n|\n|Munson wrote that she posed for Bitter for a sculpture of ''Peace''<br>(pictured), but it was not the Appellate Courthouse work.<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 4\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Liberty Supported by the Law''<ref name=\"El Paso\"/><ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1548715JQ6D11.6665&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!316034~!4&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Wisconsin&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Bitter&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 Liberty Supported by the Law], from SIRIS.</ref>\n|[[File:Liberty Wisconsin SC, by Karl Bitter.jpg|100px]]\n|1906\u20131910\n|East Pediment,<br>[[Wisconsin State Capitol]]<br>Madison, Wisconsin\n|Bethel Vermont<br>granite\n|{{cvt|96|in|cm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Wisconsin State Capitol pediment (east) - Madison, WI - DSC02752.JPG|100px|right]]East Pediment:\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |Bas relief: ''Diana''<ref name=\"Munson Chapter 4\"/>\n|\n|{{circa}}1910?\n|Ballroom,<br>[[George Jay Gould I]] Mansion,<br>Manhattan, New York City\n|marble\n|\n|[[File:Diana MET 12382.jpg|100px|right]]This may have been related to Bitter's famous 1910<br>bronze of ''Diana'':\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#FFDEAD\" |''Pomona'' or ''Abundance''<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15E869QW93790.5945&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!7693~!1&ri=3&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Bitter&index=.AW&uindex=&oper=&term=Pomona&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=3 Pulitzer Fountain], from SIRIS.</ref>\n|[[File:Schevill Karl Bitter unfinished figure.jpg|100px]]\n|plaster<br>1898, 1915<br><br>bronze<br>1916<br>(by Konti)\n|[[Pulitzer Fountain]],<br>[[Plaza Hotel#Grand Army Plaza|Grand Army Plaza]],<br>Manhattan, New York City\n|bronze\n|plaster<br>{{cvt|24|in|cm|sortable=on}}<br><br>bronze<br>{{cvt|84|in|cm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:Pomona.jpg|100px|right]]''Pomona'' was a {{cvt|24|in|cm|sortable=on}} plaster maquette at<br>the time of Bitter's April 9, 1915 death.<ref name=\"Madigan\"/> Bitter's<br>widow asked [[Isidore Konti]] to complete the work,<br>which was dedicated in May 1916.<ref name=\"Madigan\"/><br><br>Munson was publicly credited as the model for<br>''Pomona'' as early as August 1916.<ref name=\"MPW\">''Moving Picture World'', vol. 29, no. 9 (August 26, 1916), p. 1355.[https://archive.org/details/mowor29chal/page/n529]</ref><br><br>Actress [[Doris Doscher]] (1882\u20131970) later claimed to have been the<br>model for ''Pomona''.<ref>Kevin C. Fitzpatrick, ''The Algonquin Round Table, New York: A Historical Guide'' (Rowman & Little, 2015), p. 185.</ref> (Bitter may have used more than one model,<br>or Konti may have used a different model.)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\" |[[Alexander Stirling Calder]]\n|''Star Maiden''<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=154870NV98Q01.6077&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!1282~!2&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Calder,+Alexander+Stirling&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 Star Figure], from SIRIS.</ref>\n|[[File:Star, for the \"Colonnade of Stars,\" Court of the Universe building, 1915 Panama Pacific International Exposition, San Francisco.jpg|alt=Star, for the \"Colonnade of Stars,\" Court of the Universe building, 1915 Panama Pacific International Exposition, San Francisco|100px]]\n|1915\n|colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#87CEEB\" |Panama-Pacific International Exposition<br><br>[[Oakland Museum]]<br>Oakland, California\n|bronze\n|{{cvt|48|in|cm|sortable=on}}\n|[[File:The story of the exposition; being the official history of the international celebration held at San Francisco in 1915 to commemorate the discovery of the Pacific Ocean and the construction of the (14579801637).jpg|100px|right]][[File:The story of the exposition; being the official history of the i